<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 8.01&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>Other
Events</u>.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">This Current Report on Form 8-K
discloses amended information about the operating segments of Protective Life
Insurance Company (&#147;PLIC&#148;) following management&#146;s decision during 2004 to move
the surety and residual value lines of business from the Asset Protection
segment to Corporate and Other. The presentation of this information does not
change PLIC&#146;s consolidated financial position or consolidated results of
operations for any period presented.</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The amended segment information is
presented in <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Business, Management&#146;s
Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</font></i>
with respect to each of the three years in the period ended December 31, 2003
(&#147;MD&amp;A&#148;), the related Consolidated Financial Statements and Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements of PLIC (&#147;Consolidated Financial
Statements&#148;), and Financial Statement Schedules, which are furnished as Exhibit
99.1, Exhibit 99.2, Exhibit 99.3 and Exhibit 99.4, respectively, to this Report.
The amended segment information is set forth in <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Business</font></i> beneath the headings &#147;Asset Protection&#148; and
&#147;Corporate and Other&#148;, in MD&amp;A beneath the headings &#147;Overview&#148; and &#147;Results
of Operations&#148;, in Note K of Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements,
and in Schedule III of the Financial Statement Schedules.&#160; The Current Report also includes an updated
Report of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm. Except as noted above,
the Consolidated Financial Statements remain unchanged from the Consolidated
Financial Statements that were filed in PLIC&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for
the year ended December 31, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 9.01&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>Financial
Statements and Exhibits</u>.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;text-indent:-39.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(c)</font><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><font face="Times New Roman">Exhibits:</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">23 &#150; Report of Independent
Registered Public Accounting Firm</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">99.1 &#150; Business</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">99.2 - Management&#146;s Discussion and
Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">99.3 - Consolidated Financial
Statements and Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 57.75pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">99.4 - Financial Statement Schedules</font></p>

<body lang="EN-US">

<div>

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Exhibit 23</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">To the Directors and Share Owner of</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective Life Insurance Company:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In our opinion, the consolidated financial
statements present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of
Protective Life Insurance Company and its subsidiaries at December 31, 2003 and
2002, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the
three years in the period ended December 31, 2003 in conformity with accounting
principles generally accepted in the United States of America.&#160; In addition, in our opinion, the financial
statement schedules present fairly, in all material respects, the information
set forth therein when read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements.&#160; These financial statements and financial
statement schedules are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management; our
responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements and
financial statement schedules based on our audits. We conducted our audits of
these statements in accordance with the standards of the Public Company
Accounting Oversight Board (United States), which require that we plan and
perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial
statements are free of material misstatement. An audit includes examining, on a
test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial
statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates
made by management, and evaluating the overall financial statement
presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our
opinion.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As discussed in Note A of the Notes to the
Consolidated Financial Statements, effective January 1, 2002, the Company
adopted Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 142,&#160; Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets and
effective January 1, 2001, the Company adopted Statement of Financial
Accounting Standards No. 133,&#160; Accounting
for Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<DOCUMENT>
<TYPE>EX-99.1
<SEQUENCE>3
<FILENAME>a04-15437_1ex99d1.htm
<DESCRIPTION>EX-99.1
<TEXT>
<html>

<head>





</head>

<body lang="EN-US" link="blue" vlink="purple">

<div>

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Exhibit 99.1</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Business</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective Life Insurance Company (Protective), a stock life insurance
company, was founded in 1907.&#160; Protective
is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Protective Life Corporation (PLC), an insurance
holding company whose common stock is traded on the New York Stock Exchange
(symbol: PL).&#160; Protective provides
financial services through the production, distribution, and administration of
insurance and investment products.&#160;
Unless the context otherwise requires, &#147;Protective&#148; refers to the consolidated
group of Protective Life Insurance Company and its subsidiaries.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective operates several business segments each having a strategic
focus.&#160; An operating segment is generally
distinguished by products and/or channels of distribution.&#160; Protective&#146;s operating segments are Life
Marketing, Acquisitions, Annuities, Stable Value Products and Asset Protection.
Protective also has an additional segment referred to as Corporate and Other.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Additional information concerning Protective&#146;s segments may be found in
&#147;Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of
Operations&#148; in Item 7 and in Note K to Consolidated Financial Statements in
Item 8 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.&#160;
The information incorporated herein by reference is also electronically
accessible through the Internet from the &#147;Edgar Database of Corporate
Information&#148; on the Securities and Exchange Commission&#146;s World Wide Web site
(www.sec.gov).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the following paragraphs, Protective reports sales and new capital
invested.&#160; These statistics are used by
Protective to measure the relative progress of its marketing and acquisition
efforts.&#160; These statistics were derived
from Protective&#146;s various sales tracking and administrative systems and were
not derived from Protective&#146;s financial reporting systems or financial
statements.&#160; These statistics attempt to
measure only one of many factors that may affect future profitability, and
therefore are not intended to be predictive of future profitability.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Life Marketing</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Life Marketing segment markets level premium term and term-like
insurance, universal life, variable universal life and &#147;bank owned life
insurance&#148; (BOLI) products on a national basis.&#160;
The segment uses several methods of distribution for its products.&#160; One distribution system is comprised of
brokerage general agencies who recruit a network of independent life
agents.&#160; The segment also distributes
insurance products through a network of experienced independent personal producing
general agents who are recruited by regional sales managers.&#160; Also, Protective markets BOLI through an
independent marketing organization that specializes in this market.&#160; The segment also distributes life insurance
products through stockbrokers and banks, and through direct response and worksite
arrangements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows the Life Marketing segment&#146;s sales measured
by new premium.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">161.1</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.54%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="56%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:56.84%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-align:center;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2001</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.54%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="34%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:34.1%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">163.5</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.54%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

  <td width="56%" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:56.84%;">

  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.54%;">

  <td width="213" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="17" style="border:none;"></td>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Acquisitions</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Acquisitions segment focuses on acquiring, converting, and
servicing policies acquired from other companies.&#160; The segment&#146;s primary focus is on life
insurance policies sold to individuals.&#160;
These acquisitions may be accomplished through acquisitions of companies
or through the reinsurance of blocks of policies from other insurers.&#160; Forty-three transactions have been closed by
the segment since 1970, including 16 since 1989.&#160; Policies acquired through the segment are
usually administered as &#147;closed&#148; blocks; i.e., no new policies are being
marketed.&#160; Therefore, the amount of
insurance in force for a particular acquisition is expected to decline with
time due to lapses and deaths of the insureds.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\lrahman\04-15437-1\task265449\15437-1-mm.htm',USER='mchandran',CD='Dec 30 13:38 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Most acquisitions closed by the Acquisitions segment do not include the
acquisition of an active sales force.&#160; In
transactions where some marketing activity was included, Protective generally
either ceased future marketing efforts or redirected those efforts to another
segment of Protective.&#160; However, in the
case of the acquisition of West Coast Life Insurance Company (West Coast) which
was closed by the Acquisitions segment in 1997, Protective elected to continue
the marketing of new policies and operate West Coast as a component of
Protective&#146;s Life Marketing segment.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective believes that its focused and disciplined approach to the
acquisition process and its experience in the assimilation, conservation, and
servicing of acquired policies gives it a significant competitive advantage
over many other companies that attempt to make similar acquisitions.&#160; Protective expects acquisition opportunities
to continue to be available as the life insurance industry continues to
consolidate; however, management believes that Protective may face increased
competition for future acquisitions.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Total revenues and income before income tax from the Acquisitions
segment are expected to decline with time unless new acquisitions are
made.&#160; Therefore, the segment&#146;s revenues
and earnings may fluctuate from year to year depending upon the level of
acquisition activity.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows the number of transactions closed by the
Acquisitions segment and the approximate amount of (statutory) capital invested
for each year in which an acquisition was made.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2001, Protective coinsured a block of individual life policies from
Standard Insurance Company, and acquired the stock of Inter-State Assurance
Company (Inter-State) and First Variable Life Insurance Company (First
Variable) from ILona Financial Group, Inc., the U.S. subsidiary of Irish Life
&amp; Permanent plc of Dublin, Ireland.&#160;
In 2002, Protective coinsured a block of traditional life and
interest-sensitive life insurance policies from Conseco Variable Insurance
Company.&#160; Although acquisition
opportunities were investigated, no transactions were completed in 1999, 2000,
or 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">From time to time other of Protective&#146;s business segments have acquired
companies and blocks of policies which are included in their respective
results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Annuities</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s Annuities segment manufactures, sells, and supports fixed
and variable annuity products.&#160; These
products are primarily sold through stockbrokers, but are also sold through
financial institutions and the Life Marketing segment&#146;s sales force.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s fixed annuities are primarily modified guaranteed
annuities which guarantee an interest rate for a fixed period.&#160; Because contract values are &#147;market-value
adjusted&#148; upon surrender prior to maturity, these products afford Protective a
measure of protection from the effects of changes in interest rates.&#160; Protective also offers variable annuities
which offer the policyholder the opportunity to invest in various investment
accounts.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows fixed and variable annuity sales.&#160; The demand for annuity products is related to
the general level of interest rates and performance of the equity markets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\lrahman\04-15437-1\task265449\15437-1-mm.htm',USER='mchandran',CD='Dec 30 13:38 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Stable Value Products</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s Stable Value Products segment markets guaranteed
investment contracts (GICs) to 401(k) and other qualified retirement savings
plans.&#160; GICs are generally contracts
which specify a return on deposits for a specified period and often provide
flexibility for withdrawals at book value in keeping with the benefits provided
by the plan.&#160; The demand for GICs is
related to the relative attractiveness of the &#147;fixed rate&#148; investment option in
a 401(k) plan compared to the equity-based investment options available to plan
participants.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The segment also markets fixed and floating rate funding agreements
directly to the trustees of municipal bond proceeds, institutional investors,
bank trust departments and money market funds, and sells funding agreements to
special purpose entities that in turn issue notes or certificates in smaller,
transferable denominations.&#160; During the
fourth quarter of 2003, Protective registered a funding agreement-backed notes
program with the SEC.&#160; Through this
program, Protective is able to offer notes to both institutional and retail
investors.&#160; The segment&#146;s funding
agreement-backed notes complement Protective&#146;s overall asset-liability
management in that the terms of the funding agreements may be tailored to the
needs of the seller, as opposed to the needs of the buyer, and more so in a
retail program.&#160; The segment had sales of
$450 million under this program in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s emphasis is on a consistent and disciplined approach to
product pricing and asset/liability management, careful underwriting of early
withdrawal risks and maintaining low distribution and administration
costs.&#160; Most GIC contracts and funding
agreements written by Protective have maturities of three to seven years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows the stable value products sales.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="60%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:60.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="21%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:21.04%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Year Ended<br>
  December 31</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="3%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:3.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="23%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">GICs</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="3%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:3.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="23%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.0%;">

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The rate of growth in account balances is affected by the amount of
maturing contracts relative to the amount of sales.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Asset Protection</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Asset Protection segment markets extended service contracts and
credit life and disability insurance to protect consumers&#146; investments in
automobiles and watercraft.&#160; The
segment&#146;s products are primarily marketed through a national network of 2,500
automobile and marine dealers.&#160; The Asset
Protection segment has also offered credit insurance through banks and consumer
finance companies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective entered into an agreement in 2003, under the terms of which
an unaffiliated company assumed the administration and marketing
responsibilities for a portion of the Asset Protection segment&#146;s financial
institutions credit business that was based in Raleigh, North Carolina.&#160; Protective is reviewing strategic
alternatives for certain under-performing product lines in the Asset Protection
segment.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2000, Protective acquired the Lyndon Insurance Group (Lyndon) from Frontier
Insurance Group.&#160; Lyndon markets a
variety of specialty insurance products, including credit insurance and vehicle
and marine extended service contracts.&#160;
Lyndon distributes products on a national basis through financial
institutions and automobile dealers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective is the fifth largest writer of credit insurance in the
United States according to industry surveys.&#160;
These policies cover consumer loans made by financial institutions
located primarily in the southeastern United States and automobile dealers
throughout the United States.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

sales measured by new premium including the sales of Lyndon since the date of
acquisition.</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Year Ended<br>
  December 31</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.0%;">

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2003, approximately 58% of the segment&#146;s sales were through the
automobile dealer distribution channel, and approximately 42% of sales were
extended service contracts.&#160; A portion of
the sales and resulting premium are reinsured with producer-owned reinsurers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Corporate and Other</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has an additional segment referred to as Corporate and
Other.&#160; The Corporate and Other segment
primarily consists of net investment income and expenses not attributable to
the other business segments described above (including net investment income on
unallocated capital and interest on substantially all debt).&#160; This segment also includes earnings from
several small non-strategic lines of business (mostly cancer insurance,
residual value insurance, surety insurance and group annuities), and various
investment-related transactions.&#160; The
earnings of this segment may fluctuate from year to year.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Discontinued Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December 31, 2001, Protective completed the sale to Fortis, Inc. of
substantially all of its Dental Benefits Division (Dental Division), and
discontinued other remaining Dental Division operations, primarily other health
insurance lines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Investments</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The types of assets in
which Protective may invest are influenced by various state laws which
prescribe qualified investment assets.&#160;
Within the parameters of these laws, Protective invests its assets
giving consideration to such factors as liquidity needs, investment quality,
investment return, matching of assets and liabilities, and the overall
composition of the investment portfolio by asset type and credit exposure.&#160; For further information regarding
Protective&#146;s investments, the maturity of and the concentration of risk among
Protective&#146;s invested assets, derivative financial instruments, and liquidity,
see Notes A and C to the Consolidated Financial Statements, and &#147;<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial
Condition and Results of Operations</font></i>,&#148; located in Items 8 and 7,
respectively, in this Annual Report on Form 10-K.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A significant portion of Protective&#146;s bond portfolio is invested in
mortgage-backed securities.&#160;
Mortgage-backed securities are constructed from pools of residential
mortgages, and may have cash flow volatility as a result of changes in the rate
at which prepayments of principal occur with respect to the underlying
loans.&#160; Prepayments of principal on the
underlying residential loans can be expected to accelerate with decreases in
interest rates and diminish with increases in interest rates.&#160; Protective has not invested in the higher
risk tranches of mortgage-backed securities (except mortgage-backed securities
issued in securitization transactions sponsored by Protective).&#160; In addition, Protective has entered into
hedging transactions to reduce the volatility in market value of its
mortgage-backed securities.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The table below shows a breakdown of Protective&#146;s mortgage-backed
securities portfolio by type at December&nbsp;31, 2003.&#160; Planned amortization class securities (PACs)
pay down according to a schedule.&#160;
Targeted amortization class securities (TACs) pay down in amounts
approximating a targeted schedule.&#160;
Non-Accelerated Security (NAS) receive no principal payments in the
first five years, after which NAS receive an increasing percentage of pro rata
principal payments until the tenth year, after which NAS receive principal as
principal of the underlying mortgages is received.&#160; All of these types of structured mortgage-backed
securities give Protective some measure of protection against both prepayment
and extension risk.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Accretion directed securities have a stated maturity but may repay more
quickly.&#160; Sequential receive scheduled
payments in order until each class is paid off.&#160;
Pass through securities receive principal as principal of the underlying
mortgages is received.&#160; The CMBS are
commercial mortgage-backed securities issued in securitization transactions
sponsored by Protective, in which Protective securitized portions of its
mortgage loan portfolio.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective obtains ratings of its fixed maturities from Moody&#146;s
Investors Service, Inc. (Moody&#146;s) and Standard &amp; Poor&#146;s Corporation
(S&amp;P).&#160; If a bond is not rated by
Moody&#146;s or S&amp;P, Protective uses ratings from the Securities Valuation
Office of the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC), or
Protective rates the bond based upon a comparison of the unrated issue to rated
issues of the same issuer or rated issues of other issuers with similar risk
characteristics.&#160; At December 31, 2003,
approximately 99% of bonds were rated by Moody&#146;s, S&amp;P, or the NAIC.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The approximate percentage distribution of Protective&#146;s fixed maturity
investments by quality rating at December&nbsp;31, 2003, is as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December 31, 2003, approximately $11.9 billion of Protective&#146;s $12.9
billion bond portfolio was invested in U.S. Government or agency-backed
securities or investment grade bonds and approximately $983.1 million of its
bond portfolio was rated less than investment grade, of which $407.6 million
are bank loan participations and $66.9 million were securities issued in
Protective-sponsored commercial mortgage loan securitizations.&#160; Protective has increased its investment in
bank loan participations over the last two years to take advantage of market
conditions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Risks associated with investments in less than investment grade debt
obligations may be significantly higher than risks associated with investments
in debt securities rated investment grade.&#160;
Risk of loss upon default by the borrower is significantly greater with
respect to such debt obligations than with other debt securities because these
obligations may be unsecured or subordinated to other creditors.&#160; Additionally, there is often a thinly traded
market for such securities and current market quotations are frequently not
available for some of these securities.&#160;
Issuers of less than investment grade debt obligations usually have
higher levels of indebtedness and are more sensitive to adverse economic
conditions, such as recession or increasing interest rates, than
investment-grade issuers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective also invests a significant portion of its portfolio in
mortgage loans.&#160; Results for these
investments have been excellent due to careful management and a focus on a
specialized segment of the market.&#160;
Protective generally does not lend on speculative properties and has
specialized in making loans on either credit-oriented commercial properties or
credit-anchored strip shopping centers.&#160;
The average size of loans made during 2003 was $3.1 million.&#160; At December 31, 2003, the average size
mortgage loan in Protective&#146;s portfolio was approximately $2.2 million and the
largest single loan amount was $19.6 million.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="58%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:58.04%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Office Buildings</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.7%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="33%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:33.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8.0</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.24%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="58%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:58.04%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Warehouses</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.7%;">

  </td>

  </td>
  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.24%;">

  </td>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retail loans are generally on strip shopping centers located in smaller
towns and anchored by one or more regional or national retail stores.&#160; The anchor tenants enter into long-term
leases with Protective&#146;s borrowers.&#160;
These centers provide the basic necessities of life, such as food,
pharmaceuticals, and clothing, and have been relatively insensitive to changes
in economic conditions.&#160; The following
are the largest anchor tenants (measured by Protective&#146;s exposure) at
December&nbsp;31, 2003:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="4%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:4.24%;">

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s mortgage
lending criteria generally require that the loan-to-value ratio on each
mortgage be at or under 75% at the time of origination.&#160; Projected rental payments from credit anchors
(i.e., excluding rental payments from smaller local tenants) generally exceed 70%
of the property&#146;s projected operating expenses and debt service.&#160; Protective also offers a commercial loan
product under which Protective will permit a loan-to-value ratio of up to 85%
in exchange for a participating interest in the cash flows from the underlying
real estate.&#160; At December 31, 2003,
approximately $382.7 million of Protective&#146;s mortgage loans have this
participation feature.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Many of Protective&#146;s
mortgage loans have call or interest rate reset provisions between 3 and 10
years.&#160; However, if interest rates were
to significantly increase, Protective may be unable to call the loans or
increase the interest rates on its existing mortgage loans commensurate with
the significantly increased market rates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December 31, 2003,
$11.8 million or 0.4% of the mortgage loan portfolio was nonperforming.&#160; It is Protective&#146;s policy to cease to carry
accrued interest on loans that are over 90 days delinquent.&#160; For loans less than 90&nbsp;days delinquent,
interest is accrued unless it is determined that the accrued interest is not
collectible.&#160; If a loan becomes over 90
days delinquent, it is Protective&#146;s general policy to initiate foreclosure
proceedings unless a workout arrangement to bring the loan current is in place.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.3pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 1996,
Protective sold approximately $554 million of its mortgage loans in a securitization
transaction.&#160; In 1997, Protective sold
approximately $445 million of its loans in a second securitization
transaction.&#160; In 1998 Protective
securitized $146 million of its mortgage loans and in 1999 Protective
securitized $263 million.&#160; The securitizations&#146;
senior tranches were sold, and Protective retained the junior tranches.&#160; Protective continues to service the
securitized mortgage loans.&#160; At December
31, 2003, Protective had investments related to retained beneficial interests
of mortgage loan securitizations of $283.6 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As a general rule,
Protective does not invest directly in real estate.&#160; The investment real estate held by Protective
consists largely of properties obtained through foreclosures or the acquisition
of other insurance companies.&#160; In
Protective&#146;s experience, the appraised value of a foreclosed property often
approximates the mortgage loan balance on the property plus costs of
foreclosure.&#160; Also, foreclosed properties
often generate a positive cash flow enabling Protective to hold and manage the
property until the property can be profitably sold.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Life Insurance in Force</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows
life insurance sales by face amount and life insurance in force.</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 29.45pt;text-indent:-29.45pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>On
December 31, 2001, Protective completed the sale of substantially all of its
Dental Division, with which the group products are associated.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 29.45pt;text-indent:-29.45pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Reinsurance
assumed has been included; reinsurance ceded (2003 - $292,740,795; 2002 -
$219,025,215; 2001-$171,449,182; 2000-$128,374,583; 1999-$92,566,755) has not
been deducted.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The ratio of voluntary
terminations of individual life insurance to mean individual life insurance in
force, which is determined by dividing the amount of insurance terminated due
to lapses during the year by the mean of the insurance in force at the
beginning and end of the year, adjusted for the timing of major acquisitions
was:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Fixed annuity account
balances increased in 2001 due to the acquisition of Inter-State and First
Variable.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Underwriting</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The underwriting policies
of Protective and its insurance subsidiaries are established by
management.&#160; With respect to individual
insurance, Protective and its insurance subsidiaries use information from the
application and, in some cases, inspection reports, attending physician
statements, or medical examinations to determine whether a policy should be
issued as applied for, rated, or rejected.&#160;
Medical examinations of applicants are required for individual life
insurance in excess of certain prescribed amounts (which vary based on the type
of insurance) and for most individual insurance applied for by applicants over
age 50.&#160; In the case of &#147;simplified
issue&#148; policies, which are issued primarily through the Asset Protection
segment and the Life Marketing segment in the payroll deduction market,
coverage is rejected if the responses to certain health questions contained in the
application indicate adverse health of the applicant.&#160; For other than &#147;simplified issue&#148; policies,
medical examinations are requested of any applicant, regardless of age and
amount of requested coverage, if an examination is deemed necessary to underwrite
the risk.&#160; Substandard risks may be
referred to reinsurers for full or partial reinsurance of the substandard risk.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries require blood samples to be drawn with individual
insurance applications above certain face amounts ranging from $100,000 to
$250,000 based on the applicant&#146;s age, except in the worksite and BOLI markets
where no blood testing is required.&#160;
Blood samples are tested for a wide range of chemical values and are
screened for antibodies to the HIV virus.&#160;
Applications also contain questions permitted by law regarding the HIV
virus which must be answered by the proposed insureds.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Reinsurance Ceded</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries cede insurance to other insurance companies.&#160; The ceding insurance company remains liable
with respect to ceded insurance should any reinsurer fail to meet the
obligations assumed by it.&#160; Protective
sets a limit on the amount of insurance retained on the life of any one person.&#160; In the individual lines it will not retain
more than $500,000, including accidental death benefits, on any one life.&#160; In many cases the retention is less.&#160; At December 31, 2003, Protective had
insurance in force of $346.5 billion of which approximately $292.7 billion was
ceded to reinsurers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Over the past several
years, Protective&#146;s reinsurers have reduced the net cost of reinsurance to
Protective.&#160; Consequently, Protective has
increased the amount of reinsurance which it cedes on newly-written individual life
insurance policies, and has also ceded a portion of the mortality risk of
existing business of the Life Marketing and Acquisitions business segments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective also has used
reinsurance in the sale of the Dental Division and to reinsure fixed annuities
in conjunction with the acquisition of two small insurers and for reinsuring
guaranteed minimum death benefit (GMDB) claims in its variable annuity
contracts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Policy Liabilities and Accruals</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The applicable insurance
laws under which Protective and its insurance subsidiaries operate require that
each insurance company report policy liabilities to meet future obligations on
the outstanding policies.&#160; These
liabilities are the amounts which, with the additional premiums to be received
and interest thereon compounded annually at certain assumed rates, are
calculated in accordance with applicable law to be sufficient to meet the
various policy and contract obligations as they mature.&#160; These laws specify that the liabilities shall
not be less than liabilities calculated using certain named mortality tables
and interest rates.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\lrahman\04-15437-1\task265449\15437-1-mm.htm',USER='mchandran',CD='Dec 30 13:38 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The policy liabilities
and accruals carried in Protective&#146;s financial reports presented on the basis
of accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America
(GAAP) differ from those specified by the laws of the various states and
carried in the insurance subsidiaries&#146; statutory financial statements
(presented on the basis of statutory accounting principles mandated by state
insurance regulations).&#160; For policy liabilities
other than those for universal life policies, annuity contracts, GICs, and
funding agreements, these differences arise from the use of mortality and
morbidity tables and interest rate assumptions which are deemed to be more
appropriate for financial reporting purposes than those required for statutory
accounting purposes; from the introduction of lapse assumptions into the
calculation; and from the use of the net level premium method on all
business.&#160; Policy liabilities for
universal life policies, annuity contracts, GICs, and funding agreements are
carried in Protective&#146;s financial reports at the account value of the policy or
contract plus accrued interest.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Federal Income Tax Consequences</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Existing federal laws and
regulations affect the taxation of Protective&#146;s products. Income tax payable by
policyholders on investment earnings is deferred during the accumulation period
of certain life insurance and annuity products.&#160;
Congress has from time to time considered proposals that, if enacted,
would have had an adverse impact on the federal income tax treatment of such
products, or would increase the tax-deferred status of competing products.&#160; In addition, life insurance products are
often used to fund estate tax obligations.&#160;
Legislation has recently been enacted that would over time, reduce and
eventually eliminate the estate tax.&#160; If
the estate tax is significantly reduced or eliminated, the demand for certain
life insurance products could be adversely affected.&#160; Protective cannot predict what tax
initiatives may be enacted which could adversely affect Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries are taxed by the federal government in a manner similar
to companies in other industries.&#160;
However, certain restrictions on consolidating recently acquired life
insurance companies and on consolidating life insurance company income with
non-insurance income are applicable to Protective; thus, Protective is not able
to consolidate all of the operating results of its subsidiaries for federal
income tax purposes.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under pre-1984 tax law,
certain income of Protective was not taxed currently, but was accumulated in a
memorandum account designated as &#147;Policyholders&#146; Surplus&#148; to be taxed only when
such income was distributed to share owners or when certain limits on
accumulated amounts were exceeded.&#160;
Consistent with current tax law, amounts accumulated in Policyholders&#146;
Surplus have been carried forward, although no accumulated income may be added
to these accounts.&#160; As of December 31,
2003, the aggregate accumulation in the Policyholders&#146; Surplus account was
$70.5&nbsp;million.&#160; Under current income
tax laws, Protective does not anticipate paying income tax on amounts in the
Policyholders&#146; Surplus accounts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Competition</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Life and health insurance
is a mature industry.&#160; In recent years,
the industry has experienced little growth in life insurance sales, though the
aging population has increased the demand for retirement savings products.&#160; Life and health insurance is a highly
competitive industry.&#160; Protective
encounters significant competition in all lines of business from other
insurance companies, many of which have greater financial resources than
Protective, as well as competition from other providers of financial
services.&#160; Competition could result in,
among other things, lower sales or higher lapses of existing products.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The insurance industry is
consolidating, with larger, potentially more efficient organizations emerging
from consolidation. Participants in certain of Protective&#146;s independent
distribution channels are also consolidating into larger organizations.&#160; Some mutual insurance companies are
converting to stock ownership which will give them greater access to capital
markets.&#160; Additionally, commercial banks,
insurance companies, and investment banks may now combine, provided certain
requirements are satisfied.&#160; The ability
of banks to increase their securities-related business or to affiliate with
insurance companies may materially and adversely affect sales of all of
Protective&#146;s products by substantially increasing the number and financial strength
of potential competitors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s ability to
compete is dependent upon, among other things, its ability to attract and
retain distribution channels to market its insurance and investment products,
its ability to develop competitive and profitable products, its ability to
maintain low unit costs, and its maintenance of strong ratings from rating
agencies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Regulation</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries are subject to government regulation in each of the
states in which they conduct business.&#160;
Such regulation is vested in state agencies having broad administrative
power dealing with many aspects of Protective&#146;s business, which may include
premium rates, marketing practices, advertising, privacy, policy</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\lrahman\04-15437-1\task265449\15437-1-mm.htm',USER='mchandran',CD='Dec 30 13:38 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">forms, and capital adequacy, and is concerned primarily with the
protection of policyholders and other customers rather than share owners.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A life insurance
company&#146;s statutory capital is computed according to rules prescribed by the
National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) as modified by the
insurance company&#146;s state of domicile.&#160;
Statutory accounting rules are different from GAAP and are intended to
reflect a more conservative view; for example, requiring immediate expensing of
policy acquisition costs and through the use of more conservative computations
of policy liabilities.&#160; The NAIC&#146;s
risk-based capital requirements require insurance companies to calculate and
report information under a risk-based capital formula.&#160; These requirements are intended to allow
insurance regulators to identify inadequately capitalized insurance companies
based upon the types and mixtures of risks inherent in the insurer&#146;s
operations.&#160; The formula includes
components for asset risk, liability risk, interest rate exposure, and other
factors.&#160; Based upon the December 31,
2003 statutory financial reports, Protective and its insurance subsidiaries are
adequately capitalized under the formula.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries are required to file detailed annual reports with the
supervisory agencies in each of the jurisdictions in which they do business and
their business and accounts are subject to examination by such agencies at any
time.&#160; Under the rules of the NAIC,
insurance companies are examined periodically (generally every three to five
years) by one or more of the supervisory agencies on behalf of the states in
which they do business.&#160; To date, no such
insurance department examinations have produced any significant adverse
findings regarding Protective or any insurance company subsidiary of
Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under insurance guaranty
fund laws in most states, insurance companies doing business in such a state
can be assessed up to prescribed limits for policyholder losses incurred by
insolvent or failed insurance companies.&#160;
Although Protective cannot predict the amount of any future assessments,
most insurance guaranty fund laws currently provide that an assessment may be
excused or deferred if it would threaten an insurer&#146;s financial strength.&#160; Protective and its insurance subsidiaries
were assessed immaterial amounts in 2003, which will be partially offset by
credits against future state premium taxes.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition, many states,
including the states in which Protective and its insurance subsidiaries are
domiciled, have enacted legislation or adopted regulations regarding insurance
holding company systems.&#160; These laws
require registration of and periodic reporting by insurance companies domiciled
within the jurisdiction which control or are controlled by other corporations
or persons so as to constitute an insurance holding company system.&#160; These laws also affect the acquisition of
control of insurance companies as well as transactions between insurance
companies and companies controlling them.&#160;
Most states, including Tennessee, where Protective is domiciled, require
administrative approval of the acquisition of control of an insurance company
domiciled in the state or the acquisition of control of an insurance holding
company whose insurance subsidiary is incorporated in the state.&#160; In Tennessee, the acquisition of 10% of the
voting securities of an entity is generally deemed to be the acquisition of
control for the purpose of the insurance holding company statute and requires
not only the filing of detailed information concerning the acquiring parties
and the plan of acquisition, but also administrative approval prior to the
acquisition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries are subject to various state statutory and regulatory
restrictions on the insurance subsidiaries&#146; ability to pay dividends to
PLC.&#160; In general, dividends up to
specified levels are considered ordinary and may be paid without prior
approval.&#160; Dividends in larger amounts
are subject to approval by the insurance commissioner of the state of
domicile.&#160; The maximum amount that would
qualify as ordinary dividends to PLC by Protective in 2004 is estimated to be
$293.8 million.&#160; No assurance can be
given that more stringent restrictions will not be adopted from time to time by
states in which Protective and its insurance subsidiaries are domiciled; such
restrictions could have the effect, under certain circumstances, of
significantly reducing dividends or other amounts payable to PLC by such
subsidiaries without affirmative prior approval by state regulatory
authorities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries may be subject to regulation by the United States
Department of Labor when providing a variety of products and services to
employee benefit plans governed by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act
(ERISA).&#160; Severe penalties are imposed
for breach of duties under ERISA.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
