<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain policies,
contracts and annuities offered by Protective and its subsidiaries are subject
to regulation under the federal securities laws administered by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.&#160; The federal
securities laws contain regulatory restrictions and criminal, administrative
and private remedial provisions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Additional issues related
to regulation of Protective and its insurance subsidiaries are discussed in <i><font style="font-style:italic;">&#147;Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and
Results of Operations&#148;</font></i> included herein.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Employees</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December 31, 2003
Protective had approximately 1,437 authorized positions, including
approximately 973 in Birmingham, Alabama.&#160;
Most employees are covered by contributory major medical, dental, group
life, and long-term disability insurance plans.&#160;
The cost of these benefits to Protective in 2003 was approximately $4.3
million.&#160; In addition, substantially all
of the employees are covered by a pension plan. Protective also matches
employee contributions to its 401(k) Plan and makes discretionary profit
sharing contributions for employees not otherwise covered by a bonus or sales
incentive plan.&#160; See Note L to
Consolidated Financial Statements.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<body lang="EN-US" link="blue" vlink="purple">

<div>

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-align:right;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Exhibit 99.2</font></b></p>

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-align:right;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Management&#146;s
Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">This Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis should be
read in its entirety, since it contains detailed information that is important
to understanding Protective&#146;s results and financial condition.&#160; The Overview below is qualified in its
entirety by the full Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS &#150;
CAUTIONARY LANGUAGE</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">This report reviews Protective&#146;s financial condition
and results of operations including its liquidity and capital resources.&#160; Historical information is presented and
discussed.&#160; Where appropriate, factors
that may affect future financial performance are also identified and
discussed.&#160; Certain statements made in
this report include &#147;forward-looking statements&#148; within the meaning of the
Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995.&#160; Forward-looking statements include any
statement that may predict, forecast, indicate or imply future results,
performance or achievements instead of historical facts and may contain words
like &#147;believe,&#148; &#147;expect,&#148; &#147;estimate,&#148; &#147;project,&#148; &#147;budget,&#148; &#147;forecast,&#148; &#147;anticipate,&#148;
&#147;plan,&#148; &#147;will,&#148; &#147;shall,&#148; &#147;may,&#148; and other words, phrases, or expressions with
similar meaning.&#160; Forward-looking
statements involve risks and uncertainties which may cause actual results to
differ materially from the results contained in the forward-looking statements,
and Protective cannot give assurances that such statements will prove to be
correct.&#160; Given these risks and uncertainties,
investors should not place undue reliance on forward-looking statements as a
prediction of actual results.&#160; Please
refer to &#147;Known Trends and Uncertainties&#148; herein for more information about
factors which could affect future results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">OVERVIEW</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective Life Insurance Company (Protective) and its
subsidiaries provide financial services through the production, distribution,
and administration of insurance and investment products. Protective operates
five business segments.&#160; An operating
segment is generally distinguished by products and/or channels of
distribution.&#160; Protective&#146;s operating
segments are Life Marketing, Acquisitions, Annuities, Stable Value Products,
and Asset Protection.&#160; In addition,
Protective has another segment referred to as the Corporate and Other segment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2003, Protective&#146;s net income increased 47.4% to
$232.0 million compared to $157.4 million in 2002.&#160; Included in 2003 net income were net realized
investment gains of $75.0 million compared to gains of $7.6 million in 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Life Marketing segment&#146;s pretax operating income
was $160.0 million in 2003, an increase of 27.5% over the $125.4 million
reported in 2002.&#160; The increase was
primarily attributable to an increase in business-in-force.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Acquisitions segment&#146;s pretax operating income was
$96.7 million in 2003, up slightly from the $96.4 million reported in
2002.&#160; Increased earnings from recently
completed transactions were offset by the expected declining earnings from older
acquired blocks of business.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Annuities segment&#146;s pretax operating income was
$13.2 million in 2003, a decline of $1.5 million from the $14.7 million
reported in 2002.&#160; The decrease is
primarily due to interest spread compression and low sales of fixed annuities caused
by lower interest rates in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stable Value Products pretax operating income was
$38.9 million in 2003, compared to $42.3 million in 2002.&#160; Average operating spreads decreased to 96
basis points in 2003, compared to 107 basis points in 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Asset Protection segment had pretax operating
income of $16.0 million in 2003, compared to a loss of $6.7&nbsp;million in
2002.&#160; This increase in pretax operating
income was primarily due to improvements in service contract lines and charges
recorded in 2002 due to negative trends in service contract and other product
lines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Corporate and Other had a pretax operating loss of
$20.8 million in 2003 compared to a loss of $27.9&nbsp;million in 2002.&#160; An increase in investment income and improved
results from the insurance lines contributed to the change.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s accounting policies inherently require
the use of judgments relating to a variety of assumptions and estimates, in
particular expectations of current and future mortality, morbidity,
persistency, expenses, and interest rates.&#160;
Because of the inherent uncertainty when using the assumptions and
estimates, the effect of certain accounting policies</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">under different
conditions or assumptions could be materially different from those reported in
the consolidated financial statements.&#160; A
discussion of the various critical accounting policies is presented below.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective incurs significant costs in connection with
acquiring new insurance business.&#160; These
costs, which vary with and are primarily related to the production of new
business and coinsurance of blocks of policies, are deferred.&#160; The recovery of such costs is dependent on
the future profitability of the related policies.&#160; The amount of future profit is dependent
principally on investment returns, mortality, morbidity, persistency, and
expenses to administer the business and certain economic variables, such as
inflation.&#160; These factors enter into
management&#146;s estimates of future profits which generally are used to amortize
certain of such costs.&#160; Accounting for
other intangible assets such as goodwill also requires an estimate of the
future profitability of the associated lines of business.&#160; Revisions to estimates result in changes to
the amounts expensed in the reporting period in which the revisions are made
and could result in the impairment of the asset and a charge to income if
estimated future profits are less than the unamortized deferred amounts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has a deferred policy acquisition costs
asset of approximately $99.7 million related to its variable annuity product
line with an account balance of $2.2 billion at December 31, 2003.&#160; Protective monitors the rate of amortization
of the deferred policy acquisition costs associated with its variable annuity
product line.&#160; The methodologies employ
varying assumptions about how much and how quickly the stock markets will
appreciate.&#160; The primary assumptions used
to project future profits as part of the analysis include: a long-term equity
market growth rate of 9%, reversion to the mean methodology with a reversion to
the mean cap rate of 14%, reversion to the mean period of 5 years, and an
amortization period of 20 years.&#160; A
recovery in equity markets, or methodologies and assumptions that anticipate a
recovery, results in lower amounts of amortization, and a worsening of equity
markets results in higher amounts of amortization.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Establishing an adequate liability for Protective&#146;s
obligations to its policyholders requires the use of assumptions.&#160; Liabilities for future policy benefits on
traditional life insurance products require the use of assumptions relative to
future investment yields, mortality, persistency and other assumptions based on
Protective&#146;s historical experience, modified as necessary to reflect
anticipated trends and to include provisions for possible adverse deviation.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective also establishes liabilities for guaranteed
minimum death benefits (GMDB) on its variable annuity products.&#160; The methods used to estimate the liabilities
employ assumptions about mortality and the performance of equity markets.&#160; Protective assumes mortality of 60% of the
National Association of Insurance Commissioners 1994 Variable Annuity GMDB
Mortality Table to reflect improvements in mortality since the table was
derived and other factors.&#160; Future declines
in the equity market would increase Protective&#146;s GMDB liability.&#160; Differences between the actual experience and
the assumptions used result in variances in profit and could result in losses.
Protective&#146;s GMDB at December 31, 2003, are subject to a dollar-for-dollar
reduction upon withdrawal of related annuity deposits on contracts issued prior
to January&nbsp;1, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Determining whether a decline in the current fair
value of invested assets is an other-than-temporary decline in value can
involve a variety of assumptions and estimates, particularly for investments
that are not actively traded in established markets.&#160; For example, assessing the value of certain
investments requires Protective to perform an analysis of expected future cash
flows or rates of prepayments.&#160; Other
investments, such as collateralized mortgage or bond obligations, represent
selected tranches of a structured transaction, supported overall by underlying
investments in a wide variety of issuers.&#160;
Protective&#146;s specific accounting policies related to its invested assets
are discussed in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective utilizes derivative transactions primarily
in order to reduce its exposure to interest rate risk as well as currency
exchange risk.&#160; Assessing the
effectiveness of these hedging programs and evaluating the carrying values of
the related derivatives often involve a variety of assumptions and estimates.
Protective employs a variety of methods for determining the fair value of its
derivative instruments.&#160; The fair values
of interest rate swaps, interest rate swaptions, total return swaps and put or
call options are based upon industry standard models which present-value the
projected cash flows of the derivatives using current and implied future market
conditions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Determining Protective&#146;s obligations to employees
under its defined benefit pension plan and stock-based compensation plans
requires the use of estimates.&#160; The
calculation of the liability related to Protective&#146;s defined benefit pension plan
requires assumptions regarding the appropriate weighted average discount rate,
estimated rate of increase in the compensation of its employees and the
expected long-term rate of return on the plan&#146;s assets.&#160; Accounting for other stock-based compensation
plans may require the use of option pricing models to estimate PLC&#146;s
obligations.&#160; Assumptions used in such
models relate to equity market volatility, the risk-free interest rate at the
date of grant, as well as the expected exercise date.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The assessment of potential obligations for tax,
regulatory, and litigation matters inherently involve a variety of estimates of
potential future outcomes.&#160; Protective
makes such estimates after consultation with its advisors and a review of
available facts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">RESULTS
OF OPERATIONS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PREMIUMS
AND POLICY FEES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

the amount of premiums and policy fees, net of reinsurance (premiums and policy
fees), and the percentage change from the prior period:</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.38%;">

  </td>
  <td width="23%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.88%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">30.9</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.14%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="14%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:14.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-align:right;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2003</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="28%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:28.8%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 10.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="5%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:5.22%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="23%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.88%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">735,674</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.38%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="23%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:23.88%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(9.2</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.14%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr height="0">
  <td width="54" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="107" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="19" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="9" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="79" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="8" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="88" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="11" style="border:none;"></td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Premiums and policy fees were $810.0 million in 2002,
an increase of $191.4 million or 30.9% from the $618.7&nbsp;million reported
for 2001.&#160; During 2002, Protective
discovered that it had overpaid the reinsurance premiums due on certain life
insurance policies over a period of 10 years.&#160;
Protective recorded cash and receivables totaling $69.7&nbsp;million,
and a corresponding increase in premiums and policy fees, which reflected its
then current estimate of amounts to be recovered.&#160; Excluding this increase, premiums and policy
fees in the Life Marketing segment increased $29.5 million due to an increase
in sales.&#160; Premiums and policy fees in
the Acquisitions segment are expected to decline with time (due to the lapsing
of policies resulting from deaths of insureds or terminations of coverage)
unless new acquisitions are made.&#160; In June
2002, Protective coinsured a block of insurance policies from Conseco Variable
Insurance Company (Conseco).&#160; This
transaction resulted in an increase in premiums and policy fees of $18.8
million.&#160; The acquisition of Inter-State
and First Variable resulted in a $27.0 million increase in premiums and policy
fees.&#160; Premiums and policy fees from
older acquired blocks decreased $3.7 million.&#160;
Premiums and policy fees from the Annuities segment declined $2.3
million due to a decline in variable annuity management fees caused by the
general decline in the equity markets.&#160;
Premiums and policy fees related to the Asset Protection segment
increased $49.6 million due to continued higher sales in its service contracts
lines.&#160; Lower sales in other Asset
Protection lines during 2002 were more than offset by a decline in the amount
of reinsurance ceded.&#160; The decline in
reinsurance ceded was primarily due to a change in the form of a credit
reinsurance agreement in 2002.&#160; Premiums
and policy fees relating to various insurance lines in the Corporate and Other segment
increased $2.9 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Premiums and policy fees were $735.7 million in 2003,
a decrease of $74.4 million or 9.2% from 2002 premiums and policy fees.&#160; In 2003, Protective substantially completed
its recovery of all of the previously mentioned reinsurance overpayments.&#160; As a result, $18.4 million of premiums and
policy fees were recorded in 2003 related to the collection of the reinsurance
overpayment.&#160; Overall, premiums and
policy fees in the Life Marketing segment declined $21.5 million from 2002,
reflecting an increase in the use of reinsurance.&#160; Premiums and policy fees from the Conseco
transaction resulted in an increase of $7.2 million.&#160; Premiums and policy fees from older acquired
blocks decreased $17.8 million as a result of normal lapsing of policies
resulting from deaths of insureds or terminations of coverage.&#160; Premiums and policy fees in the Annuities
segment increased by $0.4 million in 2003.&#160;
Premiums and policy fees in the Asset Protection segment decreased by
$41.3 million due to reduced credit earned premiums attributable to lower sales
and the termination of non-core lines of business.&#160; Premiums and policy fees in the Corporate and
Other segment decreased by $1.4 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

  <td width="11" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="102" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="11" style="border:none;"></td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net investment income in 2002 increased $136.6 million
or 16.4% over 2001, and in 2003 increased $8.9 million or 0.9% over 2002,
primarily due to increases in the average amount of invested assets.&#160; Invested assets have increased primarily due
to acquisitions, receiving stable value and annuity deposits, and the asset
growth that results from the sale of various insurance products.&#160; The Standard coinsurance transaction and the
acquisition of Inter-State and First Variable resulted in an increase in
investment income of $57.5 million in 2002.&#160;
The Conseco coinsurance transaction resulted in an increase in
investment income of $13.3 million in 2003.&#160;
This increase was more than offset by $19.3 million decline in
investment income from older acquisitions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The percentage earned on average cash and investments
was 6.8% in 2002 and 6.1% in 2003, due to the overall decline in interest rates
on new investments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">REALIZED
INVESTMENT GAINS (LOSSES)</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective generally purchases its investments with
the intent to hold to maturity by purchasing investments that match future cash
flow needs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets forth realized investment
gains (losses) relating to derivative financial instruments and all other
investments for the periods shown:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Realized investment gains and losses related to
derivative financial instruments primarily represent changes in the fair values
of certain derivative financial instruments.&#160;
Realized investment gains and losses related to derivatives include
periodic settlements related to interest rate swaps intended to mitigate the
risks associated with certain investments, but do not qualify as hedges under
SFAS No. 133.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The sales of investments that have occurred generally
result from portfolio management decisions to maintain proper matching of
assets and liabilities. Realized investment gains related to all other
investments in 2002 of $73.0&nbsp;million were largely offset by realized
investment losses of $60.7 million. Realized investment gains related to all
other investments in 2003 of $93.4 million were offset by realized investment
losses of $26.6 million. During 2002 and 2003, Protective recorded
other-than-temporary impairments in its investments of $17.8 million and $13.6
million, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Each quarter Protective reviews investments with
material unrealized losses and tests for other-than-temporary impairments.
Management analyzes various factors to determine if any specific
other-than-temporary asset impairments exist. Once a determination has been
made that a specific other-than-temporary impairment exists, a realized loss is
recognized and the cost basis of the impaired asset is adjusted to its fair
value. An other-than-temporary impairment loss is recognized based upon all
relevant facts and circumstances for each investment. With respect to
unrealized losses due to issuer-specific events, Protective considers the
creditworthiness and financial performance of the issuer and other available
information. With respect to unrealized losses that are not due to
issuer-specific events, such as losses due to</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">interest rate
fluctuations, general market conditions or industry-related events, Protective
considers its intent and ability to hold the investment to allow for a market
recovery or to maturity together with an assessment of the likelihood of full
recovery. See also &#147;Liquidity and Capital Resources &#150; Investments&#148; included
herein.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Other income consists primarily of revenues of
Protective&#146;s direct response businesses, service contract businesses,
noninsurance subsidiaries, and rental of space in its administrative building
to PLC.&#160; In 2002, revenues from
Protective&#146;s service contract business increased $4.7 million.&#160; Income from all other sources decreased $1.8
million.&#160; In 2003, revenues from
Protective&#146;s service contract business increased $4.5 million.&#160; Income from all other sources increased $0.8
million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">INCOME
BEFORE INCOME TAX</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Consistent with Protective&#146;s segment reporting in the
Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, management evaluates the results of
Protective&#146;s segments on a before-income-tax basis as adjusted for certain
items which management believes are not indicative of Protective&#146;s core
operations.&#160; Segment operating income
(loss) excludes net realized investment gains and losses and the related
amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs and gains (losses) on
derivative instruments because fluctuations in these items are due to changes
in interest rates and other financial market factors instead of mortality and
morbidity.&#160; Periodic settlements of
interest rate swaps associated with certain investments are included in
realized gains and losses but are considered part of operating income because
the interest rate swaps are hedging items affecting operating income.&#160; Also, segment operating income (loss)
excludes any net gains or losses on disposals of businesses, discontinued
operations, and the cumulative effect of changes in accounting principles.&#160; Although the items excluded from segment
operating income (loss) may be significant components in understanding and
assessing Protective&#146;s overall financial performance, management believes that
operating segment income (loss) enhances an investor&#146;s understanding of
Protective&#146;s results of operations by highlighting the income (loss)
attributable to the normal, recurring operations of the insurance business
(i.e., mortality and morbidity), consistent with industry practice.&#160; However, Protective&#146;s segment operating
income (loss) measures may not be comparable to similarly titled measures
reported by other companies.&#160; Segment
operating income (loss) should not be construed as a substitute for net income
(loss) determined in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted
in the United States of America (GAAP).&#160; &#147;Total
income from continuing operations before income tax&#148; is a GAAP measure to which
the non-GAAP measure &#147;total operating income&#148; may be compared.&#160; Unlike total operating income, total income
before income tax includes net realized investment gains and losses, the
related amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs and gains (losses) on
derivative instruments.&#160; In the Annuities
and Stable Value Products segments operating income excludes realized
investment gains and losses and related amortization.&#160; In the Corporate and Other segment operating
income includes derivative gains related to investments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">16,019</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(6,661</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">

  </td>

  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(23,716</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.0%;">

  </td>

  <td width="57%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:57.0%;">

  </td>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Income before
income tax excluding realized investment gains and losses and related
amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font> Certain investments included in realized
investment gains and considered a part of operating income.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">LIFE </font>MARKETING</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Life Marketing segment&#146;s 2002 pretax operating
income was $125.4 million, $33.4 million above 2001.&#160; In the third quarter of 2002, Protective
discovered that it had overpaid the reinsurance premiums due on certain life
insurance policies, and indicated that it would be seeking recovery of
approximately $94.5 million from several reinsurance companies.&#160; At December, 31, 2002, Protective had
recorded cash and receivables totaling $69.7 million, which reflected the amounts
received at that date, and Protective&#146;s estimate of amounts to be recovered in
the future, based upon the information then available.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The corresponding increase in premiums and policy fees
resulted in $62.5 million of additional amortization of deferred policy
acquisition costs in 2002. The amortization of deferred policy acquisition
costs took into account the amortization relating to the increase in premiums
and policy fees as well as the additional amortization required should the
remainder of the overpayment not be collected. The Life Marketing segment&#146;s
pretax operating income thereby increased $7.2 million which is the difference
between the premiums recorded and the amount of such additional amortization.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Because the overpayments were made over a period of 10
years beginning in 1992, and had the effect of reducing the amortization of
deferred policy acquisition costs during that period, Protective believes that
no prior period results were materially understated and that no operating
trends were materially affected as a result.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to the increase from reinsurance
recoveries, an increase of $7.2 million in 2002 is attributable to</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">favorable mortality
experience, and an increase of $19.0 million can be attributed to growth
through sales.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Life Marketing segment&#146;s 2003 pretax operating
income was $160.0 million, an increase of $34.5 million over 2002.&#160; During 2003, Protective received payment from
substantially all of the affected reinsurance companies.&#160; As a result Protective increased premiums and
policy fees by $18.4 million and amortization of deferred policy acquisition
costs by $6.1 million, resulting in an increase in the Life Marketing segment&#146;s
pretax operating income of $12.3 million.&#160;
The remaining increase is attributable to growth of business-in-force
due to strong sales in 2002 and 2003 and favorable expense variances as
compared to pricing allowances.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ACQUISITIONS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the ordinary course of business, the Acquisitions
segment regularly considers acquisitions of blocks of policies or smaller
insurance companies.&#160; Policies acquired
through the segment are usually administered as &#147;closed&#148; blocks; i.e., no new
policies are being marketed.&#160; Therefore,
earnings from the Acquisitions segment are normally expected to decline over
time (due to the lapsing of policies resulting from deaths of insureds or
terminations of coverage) unless new acquisitions are made.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2002, the segment&#146;s pretax operating income was
$96.4 million, $27.2 million above 2001.&#160;
The Conseco and Standard coinsurance transactions and the acquisition of
Inter-State and First Variable resulted in a $24.7 million increase in earnings
in 2002.&#160; Earnings on older acquired
blocks of policies increased $2.4 million.&#160;
In 2003, the segment&#146;s pretax operating income was $96.7 million, $0.3
million above 2002.&#160; The Conseco
transaction contributed a $9.1 million increase in earnings over 2002, and
earnings from older acquired blocks of business decreased by $8.8&nbsp;million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ANNUITIES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Annuities segment&#146;s pretax operating income for
2002 was $14.7 million as compared to $15.1 million in 2001.&#160; Fixed annuity earnings increased $1.2 million
due to higher account balances.&#160; This
increase was more than offset by a decline in variable annuity earnings of $2.4
million due to the general decline in the equity markets. The segment&#146;s 2003
pretax operating income was $13.2 million, a decrease of $1.5 million from
2002.&#160; The decrease is primarily
attributable to spread compression and the inability to capitalize excess
expenses due to lower sales of fixed annuities caused by lower interest rates
in 2003.&#160; The segment had a $0.3 million
realized investment gain (net of related amortization of deferred policy
acquisition costs) in 2002 and a $3.8 million gain in 2003. As a result, total
pretax income was $15.0 million in 2002 and $17.0 million in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective offers a guaranteed minimum death benefit
feature (GMDB) on its variable annuity products.&#160; Protective&#146;s accounting policy has been to
calculate its total exposure to GMDB, and then apply a mortality factor to
determine the amount of claims that could be expected to occur in the coming
twelve months.&#160; Protective then accrues
to that amount over four quarters.&#160; At
December 31, 2003, the total GMDB reserve was $5.1 million.&#160; The total guaranteed amount payable under the
GMDB feature based on variable annuity account balances at December 31, 2003,
was $287.0&nbsp;million, a decrease of $252.0 million from December 31, 2002,
caused by an improvement in the equity markets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In accordance with statutory accounting practices
prescribed or permitted by regulatory authorities (which require the assumption
that equity markets will significantly worsen), the Annuities segment reported
GMDB related policy liabilities and accruals of $12.1 million at December 31,
2003, a decrease of $12.6 million from December 31, 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Although positive performance in the equity markets in
2003 allowed Protective to decrease its GMDB related policy liabilities, the
Annuities segment&#146;s future results may be negatively affected by a slow
economy.&#160; Volatile equity markets could
negatively affect sales of variable annuities and the fees the segment assesses
on variable annuity contracts.&#160; Lower
interest rates have negatively affected sales of fixed annuities.&#160; In this segment, equity market volatility may
create uncertainty regarding the level of future profitability in the variable
annuity business and the related rate of amortization of deferred policy
acquisition costs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">STABLE VALUE PRODUCTS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Stable Value Products segment&#146;s 2002 pretax
operating income was $42.3 million, $9.1 million above 2001. This increase is
due primarily to higher average account balances and operating spreads.&#160; Average account balances were $3.9 billion in
2002 as compared to $3.5 billion in 2001.&#160;
Operating spreads averaged 107 basis points in 2002 compared to an
average of 90 basis points in 2001.&#160; The
segment&#146;s 2003 pretax operating income was $38.9 million, a decrease of
$3.4&nbsp;million from 2002.&#160; Average
operating spreads were down to 96 basis points in 2003, causing the</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">decrease in pretax
operating income.&#160; The primary reason for
the spread compression was a reduction in yield caused by the high level of
prepayments in the mortgage-backed securities portfolio in 2003.&#160; The segments average quarterly account
balances increased by $189.6 million in 2003 to $4.1 billion.&#160; The segment had realized investment losses in
2002 of $7.1 million compared to gains of $9.8 million in 2003.&#160; As a result, total income before income tax
was $35.2 million in 2002 and $48.7 million in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has registered a program with the
Securities and Exchange Commission in which up to $3&nbsp;billion of secured
medium-term notes may be issued to the institutional market and InterNotes<sup>&#174;</sup>
may be issued to the retail market on a delayed (or shelf) basis.&#160; Each series of notes will be issued by a
separate trust and will be secured by one or more funding agreements issued by
Protective.&#160; Notes issued under the
program will be accounted for in a manner consistent with Protective&#146;s other
stable value products (i.e., included in &#147;stable value product account balances&#148;
in Protective&#146;s balance sheet).&#160;
Protective issued $450&nbsp;million of notes under this program in the
fourth quarter of 2003 to institutional investors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ASSET PROTECTION</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Asset Protection segment&#146;s core lines of business
are vehicle and marine service contracts and credit insurance.&#160; The results of the Asset Protection segment
have been significantly affected by general economic conditions.&#160; The segment&#146;s claims and corresponding loss
ratios have increased in the current economic environment.&#160; In addition, the segment has been exiting
certain ancillary lines of business, which are not core to either the service
contract or credit insurance businesses.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2002, as a result of the negative trends the Asset
Protection segment was experiencing, Protective performed claims experience
studies and other analyses and determined that it should increase its estimates
of policy liabilities and accruals and write off certain deferred policy
acquisition costs and receivables which resulted in a pretax charge of
$25.6&nbsp;million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Asset Protection segment had a pretax operating
loss of $6.7 million in 2002, $44.8 million lower than the pretax operating
income of $38.1 million in 2001.&#160; The
decrease included the $25.6 million charge discussed above.&#160; The segment also experienced lower service
contract administration fees of $2.8 million and lower earned credit premiums
that reduced income $5.8 million.&#160; Higher
loss ratios in the vehicle service contract line lowered earnings $2.8
million.&#160; Also, higher loss ratios in the
segment&#146;s ancillary lines led to higher losses of $5.2 million in 2002.&#160; Included in the segment&#146;s pretax loss for
2002 was $2.7 million of income related to the sale of the inactive charter of a
small subsidiary compared to $2.0 million for a charter sale in 2001.&#160; In addition, 2001 operating income included a
change in estimate of $6.7 million related to reserves in certain credit lines.&#160; All other items increased 2002 operating
income by $3.5 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The segment had pretax operating income of $16.0
million in 2003.&#160; Pretax operating income
for the segment&#146;s core lines of business was $17.0 million in 2003 as compared
to $18.4 million in 2002.&#160; Lower credit
insurance results in 2003, caused by reduced sales, were partially offset by
improved results on service contract lines in 2003.&#160; The vehicle service contract line of business
improved to contribute pretax operating income of $3.7 million in 2003, as compared
to a pretax operating loss of $2.8 million in 2002, due to improving loss
ratios caused by the effect of increasing prices in 2000 through 2003.&#160; The marine service contract line&#146;s pretax
operating income improved to $6.0&nbsp;million in 2003, $1.2 million better
than in 2002.&#160; Other core lines of
business contributed $7.3 million of pretax operating income.&#160; Included in pretax operating income in 2003,
was the sale of an inactive charter which contributed $6.9 million of income.&#160; Non-core lines of business and all other
items decreased operating income by $7.9&nbsp;million in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">CORPORATE AND OTHER</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Corporate and Other segment consists primarily of
net investment income on unallocated capital, interest expense on substantially
all debt, several small non-strategic lines of business (primarily cancer
insurance, residual value insurance, surety insurance, and group annuities),
and earnings from various investment-related transactions.&#160; In 2002, the segment had a pretax operating
loss of $27.9 million, $3.1 million more than 2001.&#160; The change relates to a $10.4 million
increase in investment income allocated to the segment, which was partially
offset by $10.3 million less income from the residual value, surety, and cancer
lines.&#160; Other items decreased income by
$3.2 million in 2002.&#160; Realized investment
gains (net of derivative gains related to investments) in 2002 were $4.1
million.&#160; As a result, the total pretax
loss in 2002 was $23.7 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2003, the segment had a pretax operating loss of
$20.8 million, $7.1 million less than 2002.&#160;
An increase in investment income allocated to the segment of $7.5
million was partially offset by a $3.5 million increase in expenses</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">related to employee
incentive plans and other corporate expenses.&#160;
In addition, earnings from the residual value and surety lines improved
by $3.1 million.&#160; Realized investment
gains (net of derivative gains related to investments) in 2003 were $32.5
million.&#160; As a result, total pretax
income in 2003 was $11.7 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Management&#146;s current estimate of the effective income
tax rate for 2004 is approximately 34.0%.&#160;
The expected increase is primarily due to the expiration of certain tax
credits.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December 31, 2001, Protective completed the sale to
Fortis, Inc. of substantially all of its Dental Benefits Division (Dental
Division) and discontinued certain other remaining Dental Division related
operations, primarily other health insurance lines.&#160; In 2001, the loss from discontinued
operations was $9.9 million (primarily due to the non-performance of
reinsurers) and the loss from sale of discontinued operations was $17.8
million, both net of income tax.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">CHANGE
IN ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLE</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 1, 2001, Protective adopted Statement of
Financial Accounting Standards (SFAS) No. 133, &#147;Accounting for Derivative Instruments
and Hedging Activities.&#148;&#160; The adoption of
SFAS No. 133 resulted in a cumulative $8.3 million charge to net income, net of
$4.0 million income tax.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">NET INCOME</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets forth net income from
continuing operations before cumulative effect of change in accounting
principle and related per share information for the periods shown:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
