</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net income from continuing operations before
cumulative effect of change in accounting principle in 2002 of $157.4 million
reflects improved operating earnings in the Life Marketing, Acquisitions, and
Stable Value Products segments and higher realized investment gains, which were
partially offset by lower operating earnings in the Annuities, Asset
Protection, and Corporate and Other segments.&#160;
Net income from continuing operations before cumulative effect of change
in accounting principle in 2003 of $232.0 million reflects improved operating
earnings in the Life Marketing, Acquisitions, Asset Protection, and Corporate
and Other segments and higher realized investment gains, which were partially
offset by lower operating earnings in the Stable Value Products and Annuities
segments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">KNOWN TRENDS AND UNCERTAINTIES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The operating results of companies in the insurance
industry have historically been subject to significant fluctuations.&#160; The factors which could affect Protective&#146;s
future results include, but are not limited to, general economic conditions and
the known trends and uncertainties which are discussed more fully below.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective is exposed to the
risks of natural disasters, malicious and terrorist acts that could adversely
affect Protective&#146;s operations.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">While</font> Protective has obtained insurance, implemented risk management
and contingency plans, and taken preventive measures and other precautions, no
predictions of specific scenarios can be made nor can assurance be given that
there are not scenarios that could have an adverse effect on Protective.&#160; A natural disaster or an outbreak of an
easily communicable disease could adversely affect the mortality or morbidity
experience of Protective or its reinsurers.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective operates in a mature, highly competitive
industry, which could limit its ability to gain or maintain its position in the
industry.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Life and health
insurance is a mature industry.&#160; In
recent years, the industry has experienced little growth in life insurance
sales, though the aging population has increased the demand for retirement
savings products.&#160; Life and health
insurance is a highly competitive industry.&#160;
Protective encounters significant competition in all lines of business
from other insurance companies, many of which have greater financial resources
than Protective, as well as competition from other providers of financial
services.&#160; Competition could result in,
among other things, lower sales or higher lapses of existing products.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The</font> insurance industry is consolidating, with larger, potentially
more efficient organizations emerging from consolidation.&#160; Participants in certain of Protective&#146;s
independent distribution channels are also consolidating into larger
organizations.&#160; Some mutual insurance
companies are converting to stock ownership, which will give them greater
access to capital markets.&#160; Additionally,
commercial banks, insurance companies, and investment banks may now combine,
provided certain requirements are satisfied.&#160;
The ability of banks to increase their securities-related business or to
affiliate with insurance companies may materially and adversely affect sales of
all of Protective&#146;s products by substantially increasing the number and
financial strength of potential competitors.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s</font> ability to compete is dependent upon, among other things, its
ability to attract and retain distribution channels to market its insurance and
investment products, its ability to develop competitive and profitable
products, its ability to maintain low unit costs, and its maintenance of strong
ratings from rating agencies.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">A ratings downgrade could adversely affect Protective&#146;s
ability to compete.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Rating</font> organizations periodically review the financial performance and
condition of insurers, including Protective&#146;s subsidiaries.&#160; In recent years, downgrades of insurance
companies have occurred with increasing frequency.&#160; A downgrade in the rating of Protective&#146;s
subsidiaries could adversely affect Protective&#146;s ability to sell its products,
retain existing business, and compete for attractive acquisition
opportunities.&#160; Specifically, a ratings
downgrade would materially harm Protective&#146;s ability to sell certain products,
including guaranteed investment products and funding agreements.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Rating</font> organizations assign ratings based upon several factors.&#160; While most of the factors relate to the rated
company, some of the factors relate to the views of the rating organization,
general economic conditions and circumstances outside the rated company&#146;s
control.&#160; In addition, rating organizations
use various models and formulas to assess the strength of a rated company, and
from time to time rating organizations have, in their discretion, altered the
models.&#160; Changes to the models could
impact the rating organizations&#146; judgment of the rating to be assigned to the
rated company.&#160; Protective cannot predict
what actions the rating organizations may take, or what actions Protective may
be required to take in response to the actions of the rating organizations,
which could adversely affect Protective.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s policy claims fluctuate from period to period,
and actual results could differ from its expectations.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s</font> results may fluctuate from period to period due to fluctuations
in policy claims received by Protective.&#160;
Certain of Protective&#146;s businesses may experience higher claims if the
economy is growing slowly or in recession, or equity markets decline.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Mortality</font>, morbidity, and casualty expectations incorporate assumptions
about many factors, including for example, how a product is distributed,
persistency and lapses, and future progress in the fields of health and
medicine.&#160; Actual mortality, morbidity,
and casualty claims could differ from expectations if actual results differ
from those assumptions.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s results may be negatively affected should
actual experience differ from management&#146;s assumptions and estimates.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the conduct of
business, Protective makes certain assumptions regarding the mortality,
persistency, expenses and interest rates, or other factors appropriate to the
type of business it expects to experience in future periods.&#160; These assumptions are also used to estimate
the amounts of deferred policy acquisition costs, policy liabilities and
accruals, future earnings, and various components of Protective&#146;s balance
sheet.&#160; Protective&#146;s actual experience,
as well as changes in estimates, are used to prepare Protective&#146;s statements of
income.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The</font> calculations Protective uses to estimate various components of
its balance sheet and statements of income are necessarily complex and involve
analyzing and interpreting large quantities of data.&#160; Protective currently employs various
techniques for such calculations and it from time to time will develop and
implement more sophisticated administrative systems and procedures capable of
facilitating the calculation of more precise estimates.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assumptions</font> and estimates involve judgment, and by their nature are imprecise
and subject to changes and revision over time.&#160;
Accordingly, Protective&#146;s results may be affected, positively or
negatively, from time to time, by actual results differing from assumptions, by
changes in estimates, and by changes resulting from implementing more
sophisticated administrative systems and procedures that facilitate the
calculation of more precise estimates.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">The use of reinsurance introduces variability in Protective&#146;s
statements of income.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The timing of
premium payments to, and receipt of expense allowances from, reinsurers may
differ from Protective&#146;s receipt of customer premium payments and incurrence of
expenses.&#160; These timing differences
introduce variability in certain components of Protective&#146;s statements of
income, and may also introduce variability in Protective&#146;s quarterly results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective could be forced to sell investments at a
loss to cover policyholder withdrawals.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Many</font> of the products offered by Protective and its insurance
subsidiaries allow policyholders and contract holders to withdraw their funds
under defined circumstances.&#160; Protective
and its insurance subsidiaries manage their liabilities and configure their
investment portfolios so as to provide and maintain sufficient liquidity to
support anticipated withdrawal demands and contract benefits and
maturities.&#160; While Protective and its
life insurance subsidiaries own a significant amount of liquid assets, a
certain portion of their assets are relatively illiquid.&#160; If Protective or its subsidiaries experience
unanticipated withdrawal or surrender activity, Protective or its subsidiaries
could exhaust their liquid assets and be forced to liquidate other assets,
perhaps on unfavorable terms.&#160; If
Protective or its subsidiaries are forced to dispose of assets on unfavorable
terms, it could have an adverse effect on Protective&#146;s financial condition.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Interest-rate fluctuations could negatively affect
Protective&#146;s spread income or otherwise impact its business.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Significant
changes in interest rates expose insurance companies to the risk of not earning
anticipated spreads between the interest rate earned on investments and the
credited interest rates paid on outstanding policies and contracts.&#160; Both rising and declining interest rates can
negatively affect Protective&#146;s spread income.&#160;
While Protective develops and maintains asset/liability management
programs and procedures designed to preserve spread income in rising or falling
interest rate environments, no assurance can be given that changes in interest
rates will not affect such spreads.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">From time to time,
Protective has participated in securities repurchase transactions that have
contributed to Protective&#146;s investment income.&#160;
Such transactions involve some degree of risk that the counterparty may
fail to perform its obligations to pay amounts owed and the collateral has
insufficient value to satisfy the obligation.&#160;
No assurance can be given that such transactions will continue to be
entered into and contribute to Protective&#146;s investment income in the future.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Changes</font> in interest rates may also impact its business in other
ways.&#160; Lower interest rates may result in
lower sales of certain of Protective&#146;s insurance and investment products.&#160; In addition, certain of Protective&#146;s
insurance and investment products guarantee a minimum credited interest rate,
and Protective could become unable to earn its spread income should interest
rates decrease significantly.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Higher</font> interest rates may create a less favorable environment for the
origination of mortgage loans and decrease the investment income Protective
receives in the form of prepayment fees, make-whole payments, and mortgage participation
income.&#160; Higher interest rates may also
increase the cost of debt and other obligations having floating rate or rate
reset provisions and may result in lower sales of variable products.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Additionally</font>, Protective&#146;s asset/liability management programs and procedures
incorporate assumptions about the relationship between short-term and long-term
interest rates (i.e., the slope of the yield curve) and relationships between
risk-adjusted and risk-free interest rates, market liquidity, and other factors.&#160; The effectiveness of Protective&#146;s
asset/liability management programs and procedures may be negatively affected
whenever actual results differ from these assumptions.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In general terms,
Protective&#146;s results are improved when the yield curve is positively sloped
(i.e., when long-term interest rates are higher than short-term interest
rates), and will be adversely affected by a flat or negatively sloped curve.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Equity market volatility could negatively impact
Protective&#146;s business.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The</font> amount of policy fees received from variable products is affected
by the performance of the equity markets, increasing or decreasing as markets
rise or fall.&#160; Equity market volatility
can also affect the profitability of variable products in other ways.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The</font> amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs relating to
variable products and the estimated cost of providing guaranteed minimum death
benefits incorporate various assumptions about the overall performance of
equity markets over certain time periods.&#160;
The rate of amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs and the
estimated cost of providing guaranteed minimum death benefits could increase if
equity market performance is worse than assumed.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">A deficiency in Protective&#146;s systems could result
in over or underpayments of amounts owed to or by Protective and/or errors in
Protective&#146;s critical assumptions or reported financial results.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The business of
insurance necessarily involves the collection and dissemination of large
amounts of data using systems operated by Protective.&#160; Examples of data collected and analyzed
include policy information, policy rates, expenses, mortality and morbidity
experience.&#160; To the extent that data
input errors, systems errors, or systems failures are not identified and
corrected by Protective&#146;s internal controls, the information generated by the
systems and used by Protective and/or supplied to business partners,
policyholders, and others may be incorrect and may result in an overpayment or
underpayment of amounts owed to or by Protective and/or Protective using
incorrect assumptions in its business decisions or financial reporting.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the third
quarter of 2002, Protective discovered that the rates payable on certain life
insurance policies were incorrectly entered into its reinsurance administrative
system in 1991.&#160; As a result, Protective
overpaid to several reinsurance companies the reinsurance premiums related to
such policies of approximately $94.5 million over a period of 10 years beginning
in 1992.&#160; Protective has received payment
from substantially all of the affected reinsurance companies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:0in;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Insurance companies are highly regulated and subject to
numerous legal restrictions and regulations.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
subsidiaries are subject to government regulation in each of the states in
which they conduct business.&#160; Such
regulation is vested in state agencies having broad administrative power
dealing with many aspects of Protective&#146;s business, which may include premium
rates, marketing practices, advertising, privacy, policy forms, and capital
adequacy, and is concerned primarily with the protection of policyholders and
other customers rather than share owners.&#160;
At any given time, a number of financial and/or market conduct
examinations of Protective&#146;s subsidiaries is ongoing.&#160; Protective is required to obtain state
regulatory approval for rate increases for certain health insurance products,
and Protective&#146;s profits may be adversely affected if the requested rate
increases are not approved in full by regulators in a timely fashion. &#160;From time to time, regulators raise issues
during examinations or audits of Protective&#146;s subsidiaries that could, if
determined adversely, have a material impact on Protective. Protective cannot
predict whether or when regulatory actions may be taken that could adversely
affect Protective or its operations.&#160; In
addition, the interpretations of regulations by regulators may change and
statutes may be enacted with retroactive impact, particularly in areas such as
health insurance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries may be subject to regulation by the United States
Department of Labor when providing a variety of products and services to
employee benefit plans governed by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act
(ERISA).&#160; Severe penalties are imposed
for breach of duties under ERISA.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain policies,
contracts, and annuities offered by Protective and its subsidiaries are subject
to regulation under the federal securities laws administered by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.&#160; The federal securities
laws contain regulatory restrictions and criminal, administrative, and private
remedial provisions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Other types of
regulation that could affect Protective and its subsidiaries include insurance
company investment laws and regulations, state statutory accounting practices,
state anti-trust laws, minimum solvency requirements, state securities laws,
federal privacy laws, federal money laundering and anti-terrorism laws, and
because Protective owns and operates real property state, federal, and local
environmental laws.&#160; Protective cannot
predict what form any future changes in these or other areas of regulation
affecting the insurance industry might take or what effect, if any, such
proposals might have on Protective if enacted into law.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Changes to tax law or interpretations of existing tax law
could adversely affect Protective and its ability to compete with non-insurance
products or reduce the demand for certain insurance products.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended
(the &#147;Code&#148;), income tax payable by policyholders on investment earnings is
deferred during the accumulation period of certain life insurance and annuity
products.&#160; This favorable tax treatment
may give certain of Protective&#146;s products a competitive advantage over other
non-insurance products.&#160; To the extent
that the Code is revised to reduce the tax-deferred status of life insurance
and annuity products, or to increase the tax-deferred status of competing
products, all life insurance companies, including Protective and its
subsidiaries, would be adversely affected with respect to their ability to sell
such products, and, depending upon grandfathering provisions, would be affected
by the surrenders of existing annuity contracts and life insurance policies.&#160; For example, changes in laws or regulations
could restrict or eliminate the advantages of certain corporate or bank-owned
life insurance products.&#160; Recent changes
in tax law, which have reduced the federal income tax rates on corporate
dividends in certain circumstances, could make the tax advantages of investing
in certain life insurance or annuity products less attractive.&#160; Additionally, changes in tax law based on
proposals to establish new tax advantaged retirement and life savings plans, if
enacted, could reduce the tax advantage of investing in certain life insurance
or annuity products.&#160; In addition, life
insurance products are often used to fund estate tax obligations.&#160; Legislation has been enacted that would, over
time, reduce and eventually eliminate the estate tax.&#160; If the estate tax is significantly reduced or
eliminated, the demand for certain life insurance products could be adversely
affected.&#160; Additionally, Protective is
subject to the federal corporation income tax.&#160;
Protective cannot predict what changes to tax law or interpretations of
existing tax law could adversely affect Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Financial services companies are frequently the targets of
litigation, including class action litigation, which could result in
substantial judgments.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A number of civil jury
verdicts have been returned against insurers, broker-dealers, and other
providers of financial services involving sales practices, alleged agent
misconduct, failure to properly supervise representatives, relationships with
agents or other persons with whom the insurer does business, and other
matters.&#160; Increasingly these lawsuits
have resulted in the award of substantial judgments that are disproportionate
to the actual damages, including material amounts of punitive non-economic
compensatory damages. &#160;In some states,
juries, judges, and arbitrators have substantial discretion in awarding
punitive and non-economic compensatory damages, which creates the potential for
unpredictable material adverse judgments or awards in any given lawsuit or
arbitration.&#160; Arbitration awards are
subject to very limited appellate review. In addition, in some class action and
other lawsuits, companies have made material settlement payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Group health
coverage issued through associations has received some negative coverage in the
media as well as increased regulatory consideration and review.&#160; Protective has a small closed block of group
health insurance coverage that was issued to members of an association; a
lawsuit is currently pending against Protective in connection with this
business.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective, like
other financial services companies, in the ordinary course of business is
involved in such litigation and arbitration.&#160;
Although Protective cannot predict the outcome of any such litigation or
arbitration, Protective does not believe that any such outcome will have a
material impact on the financial condition or results of operations of
Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s ability to maintain low unit costs is dependent
upon the level of new sales and persistency of existing business.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s
ability to maintain low unit costs is dependent upon the level of new sales and
persistency (continuation or renewal) of existing business.&#160; A decrease in sales or persistency without a
corresponding reduction in expenses may result in higher unit costs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Additionally, a
decrease in persistency may result in higher or more rapid amortization of
deferred policy acquisition costs and thus higher unit costs, and lower
reported earnings.&#160; Although many of
Protective&#146;s products contain surrender charges, the charges decrease over time
and may not be sufficient to cover the unamortized deferred</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">policy acquisition costs with respect to the insurance policy or
annuity contract being surrendered.&#160; Some
of Protective&#146;s products do not contain surrender charge features and such
products can be surrendered or exchanged without penalty.&#160; A decrease in persistency may also result in
higher claims.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s investments are subject to market and credit
risks.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s
invested assets and derivative financial instruments are subject to customary
risks of credit defaults and changes in market values.&#160; The value of Protective&#146;s commercial mortgage
loan portfolio depends in part on the financial condition of the tenants
occupying the properties which Protective has financed.&#160; Factors that may affect the overall default
rate on, and market value of, Protective&#146;s invested assets, derivative
financial instruments, and mortgage loans include interest rate levels,
financial market performance, and general economic conditions as well as
particular circumstances affecting the businesses of individual borrowers and
tenants.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective may not realize its anticipated financial results
from its acquisitions strategy.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s
acquisitions have increased its earnings in part by allowing Protective to
enter new markets and to position itself to realize certain operating
efficiencies.&#160; There can be no assurance,
however, that suitable acquisitions, presenting opportunities for continued
growth and operating efficiencies, or capital to fund acquisitions will
continue to be available to Protective, or that Protective will realize the
anticipated financial results from its acquisitions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Additionally, in
connection with its acquisitions, Protective assumes or otherwise becomes
responsible for the obligations of policies and other liabilities of other
insurers.&#160; Any regulatory, legal,
financial, or other adverse development affecting the other insurer could also
have an adverse effect on Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective is dependent on the performance of others.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s
results may be affected by the performance of others because Protective has
entered into various arrangements involving other parties.&#160; For example, most of Protective&#146;s products
are sold through independent distribution channels, and variable annuity
deposits are invested in funds managed by third parties.&#160; Additionally, Protective&#146;s operations are
dependent on various technologies, some of which are provided and/or maintained
by other parties.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain of these
other parties may act on behalf of Protective or represent Protective in
various capacities.&#160; Consequently,
Protective may be held responsible for obligations that arise from the acts or
omissions of these other parties.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As with all
financial services companies, its ability to conduct business is dependent upon
consumer confidence in the industry and its products.&#160; Actions of competitors and financial
difficulties of other companies in the industry could undermine consumer
confidence and adversely affect retention of existing business and future sales
of Protective&#146;s insurance and investment products.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s reinsurers could fail to meet assumed
obligations, increase rates or be subject to adverse developments that could
affect Protective.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective and its
insurance subsidiaries cede material amounts of insurance and transfer related
assets to other insurance companies through reinsurance.&#160; Protective may enter into third-party
reinsurance arrangements under which Protective will rely on the third party to
collect premiums, pay claims, and/or perform customer service functions.&#160; However, notwithstanding the transfer of
related assets or other issues, Protective remains liable with respect to ceded
insurance should any reinsurer fail to meet the obligations assumed by it.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s
ability to compete is dependent on the availability of reinsurance.&#160; Premium rates charged by Protective are
based, in part, on the assumption that reinsurance will be available at a
certain cost.&#160; Under certain reinsurance
agreements, the reinsurer may increase the rate it charges Protective for the
reinsurance, though Protective does not anticipate increases to occur with
respect to existing reinsurance contracts.&#160;
Therefore, if the cost of reinsurance were to increase or if reinsurance
were to become unavailable, or if a reinsurer should fail to meet its
obligations, Protective could be adversely affected.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Recently, certain
commentators on the insurance industry have speculated that reinsurance might
become more costly or less available in the future, which could have a negative
effect on Protective&#146;s ability to compete.&#160;
In recent years, the number of life reinsurers has decreased as the
reinsurance industry has consolidated.&#160;
The decreased number of participants in the life reinsurance market
results in increased concentration risk for insurers, including
Protective.&#160; In</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">addition, some reinsurers have indicated an unwillingness to
continue to reinsure new sales of long-term guarantee products.&#160; If the reinsurance markets for these products
further contracts, Protective&#146;s ability to continue to offer such products
would be adversely impacted.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Computer viruses or network
security breaches could affect the data processing systems of Protective or its
business partners.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A computer virus
could affect the data processing systems of Protective or its business
partners, destroying valuable data or making it difficult to conduct
business.&#160; In addition, despite our
implementation of network security measures, our servers could be subject to
physical and electronic break-ins, and similar disruptions from unauthorized
tampering with our computer systems.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Protective&#146;s ability to grow depends in large part upon the continued
availability of capital.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective</font>
has recently deployed significant amounts of capital to support its sales and
acquisitions efforts. Capital has also been consumed as Protective increased
its reserves on the residual value product.&#160;
Although positive performance in the equity markets has recently allowed
Protective to decrease its GMDB related policy liabilities and accruals,
deterioration in these markets could lead to further capital consumption.&#160; Although Protective believes it has
sufficient capital to fund its immediate growth and capital needs, the amount
of capital available can vary significantly from period to period due to a
variety of circumstances, some of which are neither predictable nor
foreseeable, nor within Protective&#146;s control.&#160;
A lack of sufficient capital could impair Protective&#146;s ability to grow.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">New accounting rules or changes to existing accounting rules could
negatively impact Protective&#146;s reported financial results.</font></i></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">Like</font> all
publicly traded companies, PLC is required to comply with accounting principles
generally accepted in the United States of America (GAAP).&#160; A number of organizations are instrumental in
the development of GAAP such as the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC),
the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB), and the American Institute of
Certified Public Accountants (AICPA).&#160;
GAAP is subject to constant review by these organizations and others in
an effort to address emerging issues and otherwise improve financial
reporting.&#160; In this regard, these
organizations adopt new accounting rules and issue interpretive accounting
guidance on a continual basis.&#160; PLC and
Protective can give no assurance that future changes to GAAP will not have a
negative impact on Protective&#146;s reported financial results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">RECENTLY ISSUED ACCOUNTING STANDARDS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 1, 2001, Protective adopted Statement of
Financial Accounting Standards (SFAS) No.&nbsp;133, &#147;Accounting for Derivative
Instruments and Hedging Activities&#148;.&#160;
SFAS No. 133, as amended by SFAS Nos. 137, 138, and 149, requires
Protective to record all derivative financial instruments at fair value on the
balance sheet.&#160; Changes in fair value of
a derivative instrument are reported in net income or other comprehensive
income, depending on the designated use of the derivative instrument.&#160; The adoption of SFAS No. 133 resulted in a
cumulative charge to net income, net of income tax, of $8.3 million and a
cumulative after-tax increase to other comprehensive income of $4.0 million on
January 1, 2001.&#160; The charge to net
income and increase to other comprehensive income primarily resulted from the
recognition of derivative instruments embedded in Protective&#146;s corporate bond
portfolio.&#160; In addition, the charge to
net income includes the recognition of the ineffectiveness on existing hedging
relationships including the difference in spot and forward exchange rates
related to foreign currency swaps used as an economic hedge of
foreign-currency-denominated stable value contracts.&#160; The adoption of SFAS No. 133 has introduced
volatility into Protective&#146;s reported net income and other comprehensive income
depending on market conditions and Protective&#146;s hedging activities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 1, 2002, Protective adopted SFAS No. 142, &#147;Goodwill
and Other Intangible Assets.&#148; SFAS No. 142 revises the standards for accounting
for acquired goodwill and other intangible assets.&#160; The standard replaces the requirement to
amortize goodwill with one that calls for an annual impairment test, among
other provisions.&#160; Protective has
performed an impairment test and determined that its goodwill was not impaired
at October 31, 2003, and 2002.&#160; The
following table illustrates adjusted income from continuing operations before
cumulative effect of change in accounting principle as if this pronouncement
was adopted as of January&nbsp;1, 2001:</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="11%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In January 2003, the Financial Accounting Standards
Board (FASB) issued FASB Interpretation No. (FIN) 46, &#147;Consolidation of
Variable Interest Entities,&#148; which was revised in December 2003.&#160; FIN 46 clarifies the application of
Accounting Research Bulletin No. 51, &#147;Consolidated Financial Statements,&#148; to
certain entities in which equity investors do not have the characteristics of a
controlling financial interest or do not have sufficient equity at risk for the
entity to finance its activities without additional subordinated support from
other parties.&#160; The effective date of FIN
46 is March&nbsp;31, 2004, for Protective.&#160;
Protective is currently evaluating the impact of FIN 46 on entities to
be consolidated as of March 31, 2004.&#160;
Although Protective does not expect the implementation of the provisions
of FIN 46, on March 31, 2004, to have a material impact on its results of
operations, had the provisions been effective at December&nbsp;31, 2003,
Protective&#146;s reported assets and liabilities would have increased by
approximately $70 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On October 1, 2003, Protective adopted Derivatives
Implementation Group Issue No. B36, &#147;Embedded Derivatives: Modified Coinsurance
Arrangements and Debt Instruments That Incorporate Credit Risk Exposures That
Are Unrelated or Only Partially Related to the Creditworthiness of the Obligor
under Those Instruments&#148; (DIG B36).&#160; DIG
B36 requires the bifurcation of embedded derivatives within certain modified
coinsurance and funds withheld coinsurance arrangements that expose the
creditor to credit risk of a company other than the debtor, even if the debtor
owns as investment assets the third-party securities to which the creditor is
exposed.&#160; The adoption did not have a
material impact on its financial condition or results of operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In July 2003, the American Institute of Certified
Public Accountants issued Statement of Position (SOP) 03-1, &#147;Accounting and
Reporting by Insurance Enterprises for Certain Nontraditional Long-Duration
Contracts and for Separate Accounts.&#148;&#160;
SOP 03-1 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15,
2003.&#160; SOP 03-1 provides guidance related
to the reporting and disclosure of certain insurance contracts and separate
accounts, including the calculation of guaranteed minimum death benefits
(GMDB).&#160; SOP 03-1 also addresses the
capitalization and amortization of sales inducements to contract holders.&#160; Had the provision been effective at December
31, 2003, Protective would have reported a GMDB accrual $0.3 million higher
than currently reported.&#160; Although the
original intent of SOP 03-1 was to address the accounting for contract
provisions not addressed by SFAS No. 97, such as guaranteed minimum death
benefits within a variable annuity contract, it appears that SOP 03-1 contains
language that may impact the accounting for universal life products in a
material way.&#160; The life insurance
industry and some insurance companies have filed letters with the American
Institute of Certified Public Accountants seeking clarification, guidance,
delay and/or revision to more appropriately reflect the underlying economic
issues of universal life insurance products.&#160;
Protective is currently evaluating the impact of SOP 03-1 on the
accounting for its universal life products.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December 31, 2003, Protective adopted SFAS No. 132,
&#147;Employers&#146; Disclosures about Pensions and Other Postretirement Benefits,&#148; as
revised by the FASB in December 2003.&#160;
The FASB revised disclosure requirements for pension plans and other
postretirement benefit plans to require more information.&#160; The revision of SFAS No. 132 did not have a
material effect on Protective&#146;s financial position or results of operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December 8, 2003, President Bush signed into law
the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act of 2003
(Medicare Act).&#160; The Medicare Act
introduces a prescription drug benefit for Medicare-eligible retirees in 2006,
as well as a federal subsidy to plan sponsors that provide prescription drug
benefits.&#160; In accordance with FASB Staff
Position No. 106-1, Protective has elected to defer recognizing the effects of
the Medicare Act for its postretirement plans under FASB Statement No. 106,
Employers&#146; Accounting for Postretirement Benefits Other than Pension until
authoritative guidance on accounting for the federal subsidy is issued.&#160; Protective anticipates that the Medicare Act
will not have a material impact on the financial results of Protective;
therefore the costs reported in Note L to the consolidated financial statements
do not reflect these changes.&#160; The final
accounting guidance could require changes to previously reported information.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">LIQUIDITY AND </font></b><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">CAPITAL</font> RESOURCES</b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s operations usually produce a positive
cash flow.&#160; This cash flow is used to
fund an investment portfolio to finance future benefit payments.&#160; Since future benefit payments largely
represent medium- and long-term obligations reserved using certain assumed
interest rates, Protective&#146;s investments are predominantly in medium- and
long-term, fixed-rate investments such as bonds and mortgage loans.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">INVESTMENTS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Portfolio Description</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s investment portfolio consists primarily
of fixed maturity securities (bonds and redeemable preferred stocks) and
commercial mortgage loans.&#160; Protective
generally purchases its investments with the intent to hold to maturity by
purchasing investments that match future cash flow needs.&#160; However, Protective may sell any of its
investments to maintain proper matching of assets and liabilities.&#160; Accordingly, Protective has classified its
fixed maturities and certain other securities as &#147;available for sale.&#148;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s investments in debt and equity securities
are reported at market value, and investments in mortgage loans are reported at
amortized cost.&#160; At December 31, 2003,
Protective&#146;s fixed maturity investments (bonds and redeemable preferred stocks)
had a market value of $12.9&nbsp;billion, which is 5.0% above amortized cost of
$12.3&nbsp;billion.&#160; Protective had
$2.7&nbsp;billion in mortgage loans at December 31, 2003.&#160; While Protective&#146;s mortgage loans do not have
quoted market values, at December&nbsp;31, 2003, Protective estimates the
market value of its mortgage loans to be $3.0&nbsp;billion (using discounted
cash flows from the next call date), which is 8.2% above amortized cost. Most
of Protective&#146;s mortgage loans have significant prepayment fees.&#160; These assets are invested for terms
approximately corresponding to anticipated future benefit payments.&#160; Thus, market fluctuations are not expected to
adversely affect liquidity.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2002, Protective&#146;s fixed maturity
investments had a market value of $11.7&nbsp;billion, which was 3.9% above
amortized cost of $11.2&nbsp;billion.&#160;
Protective estimated the market value of its mortgage loans to be
$2.8&nbsp;billion at December&nbsp;31, 2002, which was 12.2% above amortized
cost of $2.5&nbsp;billion.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mo.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:50 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows the carrying values of
Protective&#146;s invested assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:100.0%;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets forth the estimated market
values of Protective&#146;s fixed maturity investments and mortgage loans resulting
from a hypothetical immediate 1&nbsp;percentage point increase in interest
rates from levels prevailing at December&nbsp;31, and the percent change in
market value the following estimated market values would represent.</font></p>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Estimated market values were derived from the
durations of Protective&#146;s fixed maturities and mortgage loans. Duration measures
the relationship between changes in market value to changes in interest
rates.&#160; While these estimated market
values generally provide an indication of how sensitive the market values of
Protective&#146;s fixed maturities and mortgage loans are to changes in interest
rates, they do not represent management&#146;s view of future market changes, and
actual market results may differ from these estimates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective participates in securities lending,
primarily as an investment yield enhancement, whereby securities that are held
as investments are loaned to third parties for short periods of time.&#160; Protective requires collateral of 102% of the
market value of the loaned securities to be separately maintained.&#160; The loaned securities&#146; market value is
monitored, on a daily basis, with additional collateral obtained as
necessary.&#160; At December 31, 2003,
securities with a market value of $324.5 million were loaned under these
agreements.&#160; As collateral for the loaned
securities, Protective receives short-term investments, which are recorded in &#147;short-term
investments&#148; with a corresponding liability recorded in &#147;other liabilities&#148; to
account for Protective&#146;s obligation to return the collateral.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p style="line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Risk Management and Impairment Review</font></b></p>

<p style="line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective monitors the overall credit quality of
Protective&#146;s portfolio within general guidelines.&#160; The following table shows Protective&#146;s
available for sale fixed maturities by credit rating at December 31, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Limiting bond exposure to any creditor group is
another way Protective manages credit risk.&#160;
The following table summarizes Protective&#146;s ten largest fixed maturity
exposures to an individual creditor group as of December 31, 2003.</font></p>
