<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has elected to
defer recognizing the effects of the Medicare Act for its postretirement plans
under FASB Statement No. 106, &#147;Employers&#146; Accounting for Postretirement
Benefits Other than Pensions&#148; until authoritative guidance on accounting for
the federal subsidy is issued.&#160;
Protective anticipates that the Medicare Act will not have a material
impact on the financial results of Protective; therefore the costs reported in
Note L to the Consolidated Financial Statements do not reflect these
changes.&#160; The final accounting guidance
could require changes to previously reported information.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">INVESTMENTS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has classified
all of its investments in fixed maturities, equity securities, and short-term
investments as &#147;available for sale.&#148;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Investments are reported
on the following bases less allowances for uncollectible amounts on
investments, if applicable:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Fixed maturities
(bonds and redeemable preferred stocks) &#151; at current market value.&#160; Where market values are unavailable,
Protective obtains estimates from independent pricing services or estimates
market value based upon a comparison to quoted issues of the same issuer or
issues of other issuers with similar terms and risk characteristics.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Equity securities
(common and nonredeemable preferred stocks) &#151; at current market value.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Mortgage loans &#151; at
unpaid balances, adjusted for loan origination costs, net of fees, and
amortization of premium or discount.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Investment real estate
&#151; at cost, less allowances for depreciation computed on the straight-line
method.&#160; With respect to real estate
acquired through foreclosure, cost is the lesser of the loan balance plus
foreclosure costs or appraised value.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Policy loans &#151; at
unpaid balances.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Other long-term
investments &#151; at a variety of methods similar to those listed above, as deemed
appropriate for the specific investment.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Short-term investments
&#151; at cost, which approximates current market value, except collateral from
securities lending which is recorded at current market value.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-13.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Estimated market values
were derived from the durations of Protective&#146;s fixed maturities and mortgage
loans.&#160; Duration measures the
relationship between changes in market value to changes in interest rates.&#160; While these estimated market values generally
provide an indication of how sensitive the market values of Protective&#146;s fixed
maturities and mortgage loans are to changes in interest rates, they do not
represent management&#146;s view of future market changes, and actual market results
may differ from these estimates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Substantially all
short-term investments have maturities of three months or less at the time of
acquisition and include approximately $0.6 million in bank deposits voluntarily
restricted as to withdrawal.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The market values of fixed
maturities increase or decrease as interest rates fall or rise.&#160; As prescribed by generally accepted
accounting principles, investments deemed as &#147;available for sale&#148; are recorded
at their market values with the resulting unrealized gains and losses reduced
by a related adjustment to deferred policy acquisition costs, net of income
tax, reported as a component of share-owner&#146;s equity.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Realized gains and losses
on sales of investments are recognized in net income using the specific
identification basis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">DERIVATIVE
FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective utilizes a
risk management strategy that incorporates the use of derivative financial
instruments, primarily to reduce its exposure to interest rate risk as well as
currency exchange risk.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Combinations of interest
rate swap contracts, futures contracts, and option contracts are sometimes used
to mitigate or eliminate certain financial and market risks, including those
related to changes in interest rates for certain investments, primarily
outstanding mortgage loan commitments and mortgage-backed securities.&#160; Interest rate swap contracts generally
involve the exchange of fixed and variable rate interest payments between two
parties, based on a common notional principal amount and maturity date.&#160; Interest rate futures generally involve
exchange traded contracts to buy or sell treasury bonds and notes in the future
at specified prices. Interest rate options allow the holder of the option to
receive cash or purchase, sell or enter into a financial instrument at a specified
price within a specified period of time.&#160;
Protective uses interest rate swap contracts, swaptions (options to
enter into interest rate swap contracts), caps, and floors to modify the
interest characteristics of certain investments and liabilities. &#160;Swap contracts are also used to</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">alter the effective
durations of assets and liabilities.&#160;
Protective uses foreign currency swaps to reduce its exposure to
currency exchange risk on certain stable value contracts denominated in foreign
currencies, primarily the European euro and the British pound.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Derivative instruments
expose Protective to credit and market risk.&#160;
Protective minimizes its credit risk by entering into transactions with
highly rated counterparties.&#160; Protective
manages the market risk associated with interest rate and foreign exchange
contracts by establishing and monitoring limits as to the types and degrees of
risk that may be undertaken.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective monitors its
use of derivatives in connection with its overall asset/liability management
programs and procedures.&#160; Protective&#146;s
asset/liability committee is responsible for implementing various strategies to
mitigate or eliminate certain financial and market risks.&#160; These strategies are developed through the
committee&#146;s analysis of data from financial simulation models and other
internal and industry sources and are then incorporated into Protective&#146;s
overall interest rate and currency exchange risk management strategies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">All derivatives are
recognized on the balance sheet (in &#147;other long-term investments&#148; or &#147;other
liabilities&#148;) at their fair value (primarily estimates from independent pricing
services).&#160; On the date the derivative
contract is entered into, Protective designates the derivative as (1) a hedge
of the fair value of a recognized asset or liability or of an unrecognized firm
commitment (&#147;fair-value&#148; hedge), (2) a hedge of a forecasted transaction or of
the variability of cash flows to be received or paid related to a recognized
asset or liability (&#147;cash-flow&#148; hedge), or (3) as a derivative either held for
investment purposes or held as an instrument designed to mitigate the economic
changes in value or cash flows of another instrument (&#147;other&#148; derivative).&#160; Changes in the fair value of a derivative
that is highly effective as &#150; and that is designated and qualifies as &#150; a
fair-value hedge, along with the loss or gain on the hedged asset or liability
that is attributable to the hedged risk (including losses or gains on firm
commitments), are recorded in current-period earnings.&#160; Changes in the fair value of a derivative
that is highly effective as &#150; and that is designated and qualified as &#150; a
cash-flow hedge are recorded in other comprehensive income, until earnings are
affected by the variability of cash flows.&#160;
Changes in the fair value of other derivatives are recognized in current
earnings and reported in &#147;Realized investment gains (losses) &#150; derivative
financial instruments&#148; in Protective&#146;s consolidated condensed statements of
income.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective formally
documents all relationships between hedging instruments and hedged items, as
well as its risk-management objective and strategy for undertaking various
hedge transactions.&#160; This process
includes linking all derivatives that are designated as fair-value or cash-flow
hedges to specific assets and liabilities on the balance sheet or to specific
firm commitments or forecasted transactions.&#160;
Protective also formally assesses, both at the hedge&#146;s inception and on
an ongoing basis, whether the derivatives that are used in hedging transactions
are highly effective in offsetting changes in fair values or cash flows of
hedged items.&#160; When it is determined that
a derivative is not highly effective as a hedge or that it has ceased to be a
highly effective hedge, Protective discontinues hedge accounting prospectively,
as discussed below.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective discontinues
hedge accounting prospectively when (1) it is determined that the derivative is
no longer effective in offsetting changes in the fair value or cash flows of a
hedged item (including firm commitments or forecasted transactions); (2) the
derivative expires or is sold, terminated, or exercised; (3) the derivative is
designated as a hedge instrument, because it is unlikely that a forecasted
transaction will occur; (4) because a hedged firm commitment no longer meets
the definition of a firm commitment; or (5) management determines that
designation of the derivative as a hedge instrument is no longer appropriate.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">When hedge accounting is
discontinued because it is determined that the derivative no longer qualifies
as an effective fair-value hedge, the derivative will continue to be carried on
the balance sheet at its fair value, and the hedged asset or liability will no
longer be adjusted for changes in fair value.&#160;
When hedge accounting is discontinued because the hedged item no longer
meets the definition of a firm commitment, the derivative will continue to be
carried on the balance sheet at its fair value, and any asset or liability that
was recorded pursuant to recognition of the firm commitment will be removed
from the balance sheet and recognized as a gain or loss in current-period
earnings.&#160; When hedge accounting is
discontinued because it is probable that a forecasted transaction will not
occur, the derivative will continue to be carried on the balance sheet at its
fair value, and gains and losses that were accumulated in other comprehensive
income will remain therein until such time as they are reclassified to earnings
as originally forecasted to occur. In all situations in which hedge accounting
is discontinued, the derivative will be carried at its fair value on the
balance sheet, with changes in its fair value recognized in current-period
earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Fair-Value
Hedges</font></b>.&#160; During&nbsp;2003,
there were no fair value hedges outstanding.&#160;
In&nbsp;2002 and&nbsp;2001, Protective designated, as fair value hedges,
callable interest rate swaps used to modify the interest characteristics of
certain stable value contracts. In assessing hedge effectiveness, Protective
excludes the embedded call option&#146;s time value component from each derivative&#146;s
total gain or loss.&#160; In&nbsp;2002 and&nbsp;2001,
total measured ineffectiveness for the fair value hedging relationships was
insignificant while the excluded time value component resulted in a pre-tax
gain of $0 and $1.3&nbsp;million, respectively.&#160;
Both the measured ineffectiveness and the excluded time value component
are reported in &#147;Realized Investment Gains (Losses) &#150; Derivative Financial
Instruments&#148; in Protective&#146;s consolidated statements of income.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Cash-Flow
Hedges</font></b>.&#160; Protective has
entered into a foreign currency swap to hedge the risk of changes in the value
of interest and principal payments to be made on certain of its
foreign-currency-based stable value contracts.&#160;
Under the terms of the swap, Protective</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">pays a fixed U.S.-dollar-denominated
rate and receives a fixed foreign-currency-denominated rate.&#160; Effective July&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2002, Protective
designated this swap as a cash flow hedge and therefore recorded the change in
the fair value of the swap during the period in accumulated other comprehensive
income.&#160; In&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002, a
pretax loss of $66.0 million and $19.8 million, respectively, representing the
change in fair value of the hedged contracts, and a gain of like amount
representing the application of hedge accounting to this transaction, were
recorded in &#147;Realized Investment Gains (Losses) &#150; Derivative Financial
Instruments&#148; in Protective&#146;s consolidated condensed statements of income.&#160; For the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, the amount of the hedge&#146;s ineffectiveness reported in income was
a $0.3 million gain and an immaterial loss, respectively.&#160; Additionally, as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective reported an increase to accumulated other
comprehensive income of $2.7 million (net of income tax of $1.4 million) and a
reduction to accumulated other comprehensive income of $2.1 million (net of
income tax of $1.1 million), respectively, related to its derivative designated
as a cash flow hedge.&#160; During&nbsp;2004,
Protective expects to reclassify out of accumulated other comprehensive income
and into earnings, as a reduction of interest expense, approximately $3.4
million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Other
Derivatives.</font></b>&#160;
Protective uses certain interest rate swaps, caps, floors, swaptions,
options and futures contracts to mitigate or eliminate exposure to changes in
value or cash flows of outstanding mortgage loan commitments and certain owned
investments.&#160; In&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,
and&nbsp;2001, Protective recognized net pre-tax gains of $4.2&nbsp;million,
$5.3&nbsp;million, and $2.7&nbsp;million, respectively, representing the change
in fair value of these derivative instruments as well as a realized gain or
loss on contracts closed during the period.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On its foreign currency
swaps, Protective recognized a $2.6&nbsp;million pre-tax gain in&nbsp;2003
while recognizing a $1.9&nbsp;million foreign exchange pre-tax loss on the
related foreign-currency-denominated stable value contracts.&#160; In&nbsp;2002, Protective recognized a
$70.8&nbsp;million pre-tax gain on its foreign currency swaps; while
recognizing a $74.9&nbsp;million foreign exchange pre-tax loss on the related
foreign-currency-denominated stable value contracts.&#160; In&nbsp;2001, Protective recognized an
$8.2&nbsp;million pre-tax loss on its foreign currency swaps while recognizing
an $11.2&nbsp;million foreign exchange pre-tax gain on the related
foreign-currency-denominated stable value contracts.&#160; The net gain, net loss and net gain in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002
and&nbsp;2001, respectively, primarily results from the difference in the
forward and spot exchange rates used to revalue the currency swaps and the
stable value contracts, respectively.&#160; The
net gains and losses are reflected in &#147;Realized Investment Gains (Losses) &#150;
Derivative Financial Instruments&#148; in Protective&#146;s consolidated statements of
income.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.3pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has entered
into asset swap arrangements to, in effect, sell the equity options embedded in
owned convertible bonds in exchange for an interest rate swap that converts the
remaining host bond to a variable rate instrument.&#160; In&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
Protective recognized pre-tax gains of $3.0&nbsp;million, $2.0&nbsp;million,
and $12.2&nbsp;million, respectively, for the change in the asset swaps&#146; fair
value and recognized a $0.1&nbsp;million pre-tax gain, a $7.8&nbsp;million
pre-tax loss, and a $16.9&nbsp;million pre-tax loss, respectively, to
separately record the embedded equity options at fair value.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.3pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
contracts with a notional amount of $2.2 billion were in a $169.0 million net
gain position.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2002,
contracts with a notional amount of $6.0 billion were in an $83.9 million net
gain position.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s derivative
financial instruments are with highly rated counterparties.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">CASH</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash includes all demand
deposits reduced by the amount of outstanding checks and drafts.&#160; Protective has deposits with certain
financial institutions which exceed federally insured limits.&#160; Protective has reviewed the credit worthiness
of these financial institutions and believes there is minimal risk of a
material loss.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">DEFERRED
POLICY ACQUISITION COSTS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Commissions and other
costs of acquiring traditional life and health insurance, credit insurance,
universal life insurance, and investment products that vary with and are
primarily related to the production of new business, have been deferred.&#160; Traditional life and health insurance
acquisition costs are amortized over the premium-payment period of the related
policies in proportion to the ratio of annual premium income to the present
value of the total anticipated premium income.&#160;
Credit insurance acquisition costs are being amortized in proportion to
earned premium.&#160; Acquisition costs for
universal life and investment products are amortized over the lives of the
policies in relation to the present value of estimated gross profits before
amortization.&#160; Under SFAS No.&nbsp;97, &#147;Accounting
and Reporting by Insurance Enterprises for Certain Long-Duration Contracts and
for Realized Gains and Losses from the Sale of Investments,&#148; Protective makes
certain assumptions regarding the mortality, persistency, expenses, and
interest rates (equal to the rate used to compute liabilities for future policy
benefits; currently 2.6% to 9.4%) it expects to experience in future
periods.&#160; These assumptions are to be
best estimates and are to be periodically updated whenever actual experience
and/or expectations for the future change from that assumed.&#160; Additionally, relating to SFAS No. 115, these
costs have been adjusted by an amount equal to the amortization that would have
been recorded if unrealized gains or losses on investments associated with
Protective&#146;s universal life and investment products had been realized.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The cost to acquire
blocks of insurance representing the present value of future profits from such
blocks of insurance is also included in deferred policy acquisition costs.&#160; Protective amortizes the present value of
future profits over the premium payment period, including accrued interest of
up to approximately 8%.&#160; The unamortized
present value of future profits for all acquisitions was approximately $502.2
million and $542.5&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002,
respectively.&#160; During&nbsp;2003, no
present value of profits was capitalized and $40.3 million was amortized.&#160; During&nbsp;2002, $62.5 million of present
value of future profits was capitalized (relating to acquisitions and
adjustments made during the year), a $2.1 million reduction came from the sale
of a small subsidiary, and $41.3 was amortized.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The expected amortization
of the present value of future profits for the next five years is as follows:</font></p>

  <td width="115" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="12" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="116" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="9" style="border:none;"></td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">GOODWILL</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The goodwill balance at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, was $35.1 million.&#160; At October&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective evaluated its goodwill and determined that fair value
had not decreased below carrying value and no adjustment to impair goodwill was
necessary in accordance with SFAS No. 142.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">PROPERTY
AND EQUIPMENT</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property and equipment
are reported at cost less accumulated depreciation. Protective primarily uses
the straight-line method of depreciation based upon the estimated useful lives of
the assets.&#160; Protective&#146;s Home Office
building is depreciated over a thirty-nine year useful life, furniture is
depreciated over a ten year useful life, office equipment and machines are
depreciated over a five year useful life, and software and computers are
depreciated over a three year useful life.&#160;
Major repairs or improvements are capitalized and depreciated over the
estimated useful lives of the assets. Other repairs are expensed as incurred.&#160; The cost and related accumulated depreciation
of property and equipment sold or retired are removed from the accounts, and
resulting gains or losses are included in income.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property and equipment
consisted of the following at December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">SEPARATE
ACCOUNTS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The assets and
liabilities related to separate accounts in which Protective does not bear the
investment risk are valued at market and reported separately as assets and
liabilities related to separate accounts in the accompanying consolidated
financial statements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">STABLE
VALUE PRODUCT ACCOUNT BALANCES</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective markets
guaranteed investment contracts (GICs) to 401(k) and other qualified retirement
savings plans, and fixed and floating rate funding agreements to the trustees
of municipal bond proceeds, institutional investors, bank trust departments,
and money market funds.&#160; Through its
registered funding agreement-backed note program, Protective is able to offer
secured notes to both institutional and retail investors.&#160; During the fourth quarter of&nbsp;2003,
Protective registered a funding agreement-backed notes program with the
SEC.&#160; GICs are generally contracts that
specify a return on deposits for a specified period and often provide
flexibility for withdrawals at book value in keeping with the benefits provided
by the plan.&#160; Stable value product
account balances include GICs and funding agreements issued by Protective as
well as the obligations of consolidated special purpose trusts or entities
formed to purchase funding agreements issued by Protective.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002
Protective had $2.8 billion and $2.2 billion of stable value contract account
balances marketed through structured programs.&#160;
Most GICs and funding agreements written by Protective have maturities
of three to seven years.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
future maturities of stable value contracts were $1.2 billion in&nbsp;2004,
$2.0 billion in&nbsp;2005-2006, $1.4 billion in&nbsp;2007-2008, and $123.1
million after&nbsp;2008.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">REVENUES
AND BENEFITS EXPENSE</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Traditional Life, Health,
and Credit Insurance Products:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Traditional life
insurance products consist principally of those products with fixed and
guaranteed premiums and benefits, and they include whole life insurance
policies, term and term-like life insurance policies, limited-payment life
insurance policies, and certain annuities with life contingencies.&#160; Life insurance and immediate annuity premiums
are recognized as revenue when due.&#160;
Health and credit insurance premiums are recognized as revenue over the
terms of the policies.&#160; Benefits and
expenses are associated with earned premiums so that profits are recognized
over the life of the contracts.&#160; This is
accomplished by means of the provision for liabilities for future policy
benefits and the amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs.&#160; Gross premiums in excess of net premiums
related to immediate annuities are deferred and recognized over the life of the
policy.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Liabilities for future
policy benefits on traditional life insurance products have been computed using
a net level method including assumptions as to investment yields, mortality,
persistency, and other assumptions based on Protective&#146;s experience, modified
as necessary to reflect anticipated trends and to include provisions for
possible adverse deviation.&#160; Reserve
investment yield assumptions on December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 were 6.98%.&#160; The liability for future policy benefits and
claims on traditional life, health, and credit insurance products includes
estimated unpaid claims that have been reported to Protective and claims
incurred but not yet reported. Policy claims are charged to expense in the
period that the claims are incurred.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Activity in the liability
for unpaid claims is summarized as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="70%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:70.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="43%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:43.54%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.98%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Universal Life and
Investment Products:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Universal life and
investment products include universal life insurance, guaranteed investment
contracts, deferred annuities, and annuities without life contingencies.&#160; Premiums and policy fees for universal life
and investment products consist of fees that have been assessed against policy
account balances for the costs of insurance, policy administration, and
surrenders.&#160; Such fees are recognized
when assessed and earned.&#160; Benefit
reserves for universal life and investment products represent policy account
balances before applicable surrender charges plus certain deferred policy
initiation fees that are recognized in income over the term of the
policies.&#160; Policy benefits and claims
that are charged to expense include benefit claims incurred in the period in
excess of related</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">policy account balances
and interest credited to policy account balances.&#160; Interest rates credited to universal life
products ranged from 4.6% to 6.5% and investment products ranged from 2.6% to
9.4% in&nbsp;2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s accounting
policies with respect to variable universal life and variable annuities are
identical except that policy account balances (excluding account balances that
earn a fixed rate) are valued at market and reported as components of assets
and liabilities related to separate accounts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">INCOME
TAXES</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective uses the asset
and liability method of accounting for income taxes. Income tax provisions are
generally based on income reported for financial statement purposes.&#160; Deferred federal income taxes arise from the
recognition of temporary differences between the basis of assets and
liabilities determined for financial reporting purposes and the basis of assets
and liabilities determined for financial reporting purposes and the basis for
income tax purposes. Such temporary differences are principally related to the
deferral of policy acquisition costs and the provision for future policy
benefits and expenses.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">DISCONTINUED
OPERATIONS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2001, Protective completed the sale to Fortis,
Inc. of substantially all of its Dental Benefits Division (Dental Division) and
discontinued other remaining Dental Division related operations, primarily other
health insurance lines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
operating results and charges related to the sale of the Dental Division and
discontinuance of other related operations at December&nbsp;31 are as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assets and liabilities
related to the discontinued lines of business of approximately $57.1 million
remain at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">RECLASSIFICATIONS</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain reclassifications
have been made in the previously reported financial statements and accompanying
notes to make the prior year amounts comparable to those of the current
year.&#160; Such reclassifications had no
effect on previously reported net income or share-owners&#146; equity.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note B &#151;STATUTORY REPORTING
PRACTICES AND OTHER REGULATORY MATTERS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Financial statements
prepared in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the
United States of America differ in some respects from the statutory accounting
practices prescribed or permitted by insurance regulatory authorities.&#160; The most</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">significant differences
are as follows: (a) acquisition costs of obtaining new business are deferred
and amortized over the approximate life of the policies rather than charged to
operations as incurred; (b) benefit liabilities are computed using a net level
method and are based on realistic estimates of expected mortality, interest,
and withdrawals as adjusted to provide for possible unfavorable deviation from
such assumptions; (c) deferred income taxes are not subject to statutory
limitations as to amounts recognized and are recognized through earnings as
opposed to being charged to share-owners&#146; equity; (d) the Asset Valuation
Reserve and Interest Maintenance Reserve are restored to share-owners&#146; equity;
(e) furniture and equipment, agents&#146; debit balances, and prepaid expenses are
reported as assets rather than being charged directly to surplus (referred to
as nonadmitted assets); (f) certain items of interest income, such as mortgage
and bond discounts, are amortized differently; and (g) bonds are recorded at
their market values instead of amortized cost.&#160;
The National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) has adopted
the Codification of Statutory Accounting Principles (Codification).&#160; Codification changed statutory accounting
rules in several areas and was effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2001.&#160; The adoption of Codification did not have a
material effect on Protective&#146;s statutory capital.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net income and
share-owner&#146;s equity prepared in conformity with statutory reporting practices
to that reported in the accompanying consolidated financial statements are as
follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .4in;text-indent:-.4in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Consolidated</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .4in;text-indent:-.4in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
Protective had on deposit with regulatory authorities, fixed maturity and short-term
investments with a market value of approximately $74.8 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Realized investment gains

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In&nbsp;2003, gross gains
on the sale of investments available for sale (fixed maturities, equity
securities, and short-term investments) were $90.3 million, and gross losses
were $25.6 million.&#160; In&nbsp;2002, gross
gains were $73.0 million, and gross losses were $60.3 million.&#160; In&nbsp;2001, gross gains were $27.5 million,
and gross losses were $29.7 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Each quarter Protective
reviews investments with material unrealized losses and tests for
other-than-temporary impairments.&#160;
Protective analyzes various factors to determine if any specific
other-than-temporary asset impairments exist.&#160;
Once a determination has been made that a specific other-than-temporary
impairment exists, a realized loss is incurred and the cost basis of the
impaired asset is adjusted to its fair value.&#160;
During&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002 and&nbsp;2001, respectively, Protective
recorded other-than-temporary impairments in its investments of $13.6 million,
$17.8 million and $12.6 million, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The amortized cost and
estimated market values of fixed maturities at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 by
expected maturity, are shown as follows.&#160;
Expected maturities are derived from rates of prepayment that may differ
from actual rates of prepayment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective considers the
impairment of securities that have been in an unrealized loss position for less
than 12&nbsp;months to be temporary.&#160;
Protective believes that it will collect all amounts contractually due
and has the intent and the ability to hold these securities until maturity.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For mortgage-backed
securities in an unrealized loss position for greater than 12 months, $23.3
million of the unrealized loss relates to securities issued in
Protective-sponsored commercial loan securitizations.&#160; Protective does not consider these unrealized
loss positions to be other-than-temporary, because the underlying mortgage
loans continue to perform consistently with Protective&#146;s original expectations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The corporate bonds
category has gross unrealized losses of $9.1 million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
composed of $2.8&nbsp;million of electrical industry securities, $5.0 million
of transportation industry securities, and $1.3 million of other industry
securities.&#160; The aggregate decline in
market value of these securities was deemed temporary due to positive factors
supporting the recoverability of the respective investments.&#160; Positive factors considered included credit
ratings, the financial health of the investee, the continued access of the
investee to capital markets, and other pertinent information.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective had bonds which were rated less than investment grade
of $983.1&nbsp;million and $860.6 million, respectively, having an amortized
cost of $978.9 million and $960.8 million, respectively.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003, approximately
$66.9 million of the bonds rated less than investment grade were securities
issued in Protective-sponsored commercial mortgage loan securitizations.&#160; Approximately $1,956.7 million of bonds are
not publicly traded.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The change in unrealized
gains (losses), net of income tax, on fixed maturity and equity securities for
the years ended December&nbsp;31 is summarized as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  </td>

  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.8%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.32%;">

 <tr height="0">
  <td width="150" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="53" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="53" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>

  <td width="5" style="border:none;"></td>

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective participates
in securities lending, primarily as an investment yield enhancement, whereby
securities that are held as investments are loaned to third parties for short
periods of time.&#160; Protective requires
collateral of 102% of the market value of the loaned securities to be
separately maintained.&#160; The loaned
securities&#146; market value is monitored, on a daily basis, with additional
collateral obtained as necessary.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
securities with a market value of $324.5 million were loaned under these
agreements.&#160; As collateral for the loaned
securities, Protective receives short-term investments, which are recorded in &#147;short-term
investments&#148; with a corresponding liability recorded in &#147;other liabilities&#148; to
account for Protective&#146;s obligation to return the collateral.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
all of Protective&#146;s mortgage loans were commercial loans of which 75% were
retail, 8% were apartments, 8% were office buildings, and 8% were warehouses,
and 1% were other.&#160; Protective
specializes in making mortgage loans on either credit-oriented or credit-anchored
commercial properties, most of which are strip shopping centers in smaller
towns and cities.&#160; No single tenant&#146;s
leased space represents more than 2.8% of mortgage loans.&#160; Approximately 74% of the mortgage loans are
on properties located in the following states listed in decreasing order of
significance: Texas, Tennessee, Georgia, North Carolina, South Carolina,
Alabama, Florida, Pennsylvania, California, Ohio, Mississippi, and Indiana.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Many of the mortgage
loans have call provisions between 3 to 10 years. Assuming the loans are called
at their next call dates, approximately $125.0&nbsp;million would become due in&nbsp;2004,
$537.3&nbsp;million in&nbsp;2005 to&nbsp;2008, $461.5&nbsp;million in&nbsp;2009
to 2013, and $40.2 million thereafter.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
the average mortgage loan was approximately $2.2 million, and the weighted
average interest rate was 7.2%.&#160; The
largest single mortgage loan was $19.6 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For several years
Protective has offered a type of commercial mortgage loan under which
Protective will permit a slightly higher loan-to-value ratio in exchange for a
participating interest in the cash flows from the underlying real estate.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002,
approximately $382.7 million and $475.5 million, respectively, of Protective&#146;s
mortgage loans have this participation feature.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective&#146;s problem mortgage loans (over ninety days past due)
and foreclosed properties totaled $11.8 million and $16.2 million,
respectively.&#160; Since Protective&#146;s
mortgage loans are collateralized by real estate, any assessment of impairment
is based upon the estimated fair value of the real estate.&#160; Based on Protective&#146;s evaluation of its
mortgage loan portfolio, Protective does not expect any material losses on its
mortgage loans.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective had investments related to retained beneficial
interests of mortgage loan securitizations of $283.6 million and $295.7
million, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain investments with
a carrying value of $64.4 million were non-income producing for the twelve
months ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Policy loan interest
rates generally range from 4.5% to 8.0%.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-weight:bold;line-height:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note
D &#151;INCOME TAXES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s effective
income tax rate related to continuing operations varied from the maximum
federal income tax rate as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The provision for federal
income tax differs from amounts currently payable due to certain items reported
for financial statement purposes in periods which differ from those in which
they are reported for income tax purposes.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Details of the deferred

  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.04%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under pre-1984 life
insurance company income tax laws, a portion of Protective&#146;s gain from
operations which was not subject to current income taxation was accumulated for
income tax purposes in a memorandum account designated as Policyholders&#146;
Surplus.&#160; The aggregate accumulation in
this account at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003 was approximately
$70.5&nbsp;million.&#160; Should the
accumulation in the Policyholders&#146; Surplus account exceed certain stated
maximums, or should distributions including cash dividends be made to PLC in
excess of approximately $1.6 billion, such excess would be subject to federal
income taxes at rates then effective.&#160;
Deferred income taxes have not been provided on amounts designated as
Policyholders&#146; Surplus.&#160; Under current
income tax laws, Protective does not anticipate paying income tax on amounts in
the Policyholders&#146; Surplus accounts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s income tax
returns are included in the consolidated income tax returns of PLC.&#160; The allocation of income tax liabilities
among affiliates is based upon separate income tax return calculations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note E &#151;
DEBT</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under revolving line of
credit arrangements with several banks, PLC can borrow up to $200&nbsp;million
on an unsecured basis.&#160; No compensating
balances are required to maintain the line of credit.&#160; These lines of credit arrangements contain,
among other provisions, requirements for maintaining certain financial ratios,
and restrictions on indebtedness incurred by PLC&#146;s subsidiaries including
Protective.&#160; Additionally, PLC, on a
consolidated basis, cannot incur debt in excess of 40% of its total
capital.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
PLC had $25.0&nbsp;million of borrowings outstanding under these credit
arrangements at an interest rate of 1.64%.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has a mortgage
note on investment real estate amounting to approximately $2.2 million that
matures in&nbsp;2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Included in indebtedness
to related parties at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2002,was a surplus debenture
issued by Protective to PLC.&#160; The balance
of the surplus debenture was $2 million.&#160;
The surplus debenture was due and paid in&nbsp;2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective routinely
receives from or pays to affiliates under the control of PLC reimbursements for
expenses incurred on one another&#146;s behalf. Receivables and payables among
affiliates are generally settled monthly.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Interest expense on debt
totaled $1.6 million, $1.4 million, and $1.8 million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,
and&nbsp;2001, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note
F &#151; RECENT ACQUISITIONS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In January&nbsp;2001,
Protective coinsured a block of individual life policies from Standard
Insurance Company.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In October&nbsp;2001,
Protective completed the acquisition of the stock of Inter-State Assurance
Company (Inter-State) and First Variable Life Insurance Company (First
Variable) from ILona Financial Group, Inc., a subsidiary of Irish
Life&nbsp;&amp; Permanent plc of Dublin, Ireland.&#160; The purchase price was approximately $250
million.&#160; The assets acquired included
$166.1 million of present value of future profits.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In June&nbsp;2002,
Protective coinsured a block of traditional life and interest-sensitive life
insurance policies from Conseco Variable Insurance Company. These transactions have been accounted for as
purchases, and the results of the transactions have been included in the
accompanying financial statements since their respective effective dates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Summarized below are the
consolidated results of operations for&nbsp;2002, on an unaudited pro forma
basis, as if the Conseco transaction had occurred as of January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2002.&#160; The pro forma information is based on
Protective&#146;s consolidated results of operations for&nbsp;2002, and on data
provided by the acquired block, after giving effect to certain pro forma adjustments.&#160; The pro forma financial information does not
purport to be indicative of results of operations that would have occurred had
the transaction occurred on the basis assumed above nor are they indicative of
results of the future operations of the combined enterprises.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
