<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note G &#151; COMMITMENTS AND
CONTINGENT LIABILITIES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective leases
administrative and marketing office space in approximately 24 cities including
Birmingham, with most leases being for periods of three to ten years.&#160; The aggregate annualized rent is
approximately $8.0 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In&nbsp;2000, Protective
entered into an arrangement with an unrelated party related to the construction
of a building contiguous to its existing home office complex.&#160; The unrelated party owns the building and
leases it to Protective.&#160; The lease is
accounted for as an operating lease under SFAS No. 13 &#147;Accounting For Leases&#148;.&#160; Lease payments commenced upon completion,
which occurred January&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003, and is based on then current LIBOR
interest rates and the cost of the building.&#160;
At the end of the lease term, February&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, Protective may
purchase the building for the original building cost of approximately $75
million.&#160; Based upon current interest
rates, annual lease payments are estimated to be $1.5 million.&#160; Were Protective not to purchase the building,
a payment of approximately $66 million would be due at the end of the lease
term.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Under insurance guaranty
fund laws, in most states insurance companies doing business therein can be
assessed up to prescribed limits for policyholder losses incurred by insolvent
companies.&#160; Protective does not believe
such assessments will be materially different from amounts already provided for
in the financial statements.&#160; Most of
these laws do provide, however, that an assessment may be excused or deferred
if it would threaten an insurer&#146;s own financial strength.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">A number of civil jury
verdicts have been returned against insurers and other providers of financial
services involving sales practices, alleged agent misconduct, failure to
properly supervise representatives&#146; relationships with agents or persons with
whom the insurer does business, and other matters.&#160; Increasingly these lawsuits have resulted in
the award of substantial judgments that are disproportionate to the actual
damages, including material amounts of punitive and non-economic compensatory
damages.&#160; In some states, juries, judges
and arbitrators have substantial discretion in awarding punitive and
non-economic compensatory damages which creates the potential for unpredictable
material adverse judgments or awards in any given lawsuit or arbitration.&#160; Arbitration awards are subject to very little
appellate review.&#160; In addition, in some
class action and other lawsuits, companies have made material settlement
payments.&#160; Protective, like other
financial service companies, in the ordinary course of business, is involved in
such litigation or, alternatively, in arbitration.&#160; Although the outcome of any such litigation
or arbitration cannot be predicted Protective believes that at the present time
there are no pending or threatened lawsuits that are reasonably likely to have
a material adverse effect on the financial position, results of operations, or
liquidity of Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note H &#151; SHARE-OWNER&#146;S EQUITY AND
RESTRICTIONS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
approximately $1,386.9&nbsp;million of consolidated share-owner&#146;s equity,
excluding net unrealized gains on investments, represented net assets of
Protective and its subsidiaries that cannot be transferred to PLC in the form
of dividends, loans, or advances.&#160; In
addition, Protective and its subsidiaries are subject to various state
statutory and regulatory restrictions on their ability to pay dividends to
PLC.&#160; In general, dividends up to
specified levels are considered ordinary and may be paid thirty days after
written notice to the insurance commissioner of the state of domicile unless
such commissioner objects to the dividend prior to the expiration of such period.&#160; Dividends in larger amounts are considered
extraordinary and are subject to affirmative prior approval by such
commissioner.&#160; The maximum amount that
would qualify as ordinary dividends to PLC by Protective in&nbsp;2004 is
estimated to be $293.8&nbsp;million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note I &#151; PREFERRED STOCK</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC owns all of the 2,000
shares of preferred stock issued by Protective&#146;s subsidiary, Protective Life
and Annuity Insurance Company (PL&amp;A).&#160;
The stock pays, when and if declared, noncumulative participating
dividends to the extent PL&amp;A&#146;s statutory earnings for the immediately
preceding fiscal year exceeded $1.0&nbsp;million.&#160; In&nbsp;2003, PL&amp;A paid no dividend to
PLC. In&nbsp;2002, PL&amp;A paid a $50.0 thousand preferred dividend to PLC,
and PL&amp;A paid a $1.0 million preferred dividend to PLC in&nbsp;2001.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note J &#151; RELATED PARTY MATTERS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On August&nbsp;6, 1990,
PLC announced that its Board of Directors approved the formation of an Employee
Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP).&#160; On December&nbsp;1,
1990, Protective transferred to the ESOP 520,000 shares of PLC&#146;s common stock
held by it in exchange for a note.&#160; The
outstanding balance of the note, $3.4 million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
is accounted for as a reduction to share-owner&#146;s equity.&#160; The stock will be used to match employee
contributions to PLC&#146;s existing 401(k) Plan.&#160;
The ESOP shares are dividend paying. Dividends on the shares are used to
pay the ESOP&#146;s note to Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective leases
furnished office space and computers to affiliates. Lease revenues were $4.7
million in&nbsp;2003, $3.5 million in&nbsp;2002, and $4.0 million in&nbsp;2001.&#160; Protective purchases data processing, legal,
investment and management services from affiliates.&#160; The costs of such services were
$93.1&nbsp;million, $88.0 million, and $82.6 million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,
and&nbsp;2001, respectively.&#160; Commissions
paid to affiliated marketing organizations of $8.6&nbsp;million,
$8.2&nbsp;million, and $10.0&nbsp;million, in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively, were included in deferred policy acquisition costs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain corporations with
which PLC&#146;s directors were affiliated paid Protective premiums and policy fees
or other amounts for various types of insurance and investment products.&#160; Such premiums, policy fees, and other amounts
totaled $12.2 million, $16.0 million and $19.6 million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,
and&nbsp;2001, respectively.&#160; Protective
and/or PLC paid commissions, interest on debt and investment products, and fees
to these same corporations totaling $2.1 million, $1.6&nbsp;million and $5.9
million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For a discussion of
indebtedness to related parties, see Note E.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note K &#151; OPERATING SEGMENTS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective operates
several business segments, each having a strategic focus.&#160; An operating segment is generally
distinguished by products and/or channels of distribution.&#160; A brief description of each segment follows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.3pt;text-indent:-22.3pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The Life Marketing segment
markets level premium term and term-like insurance, universal life, and
variable universal life products on a national basis primarily through networks
of independent insurance agents and brokers, and in the &#147;bank owned life insurance&#148;
market.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.3pt;text-indent:-22.3pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The Acquisitions segment
focuses on acquiring, converting, and servicing policies acquired from other
companies.&#160; The segment&#146;s primary focus
is on life insurance policies sold to individuals.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.3pt;text-indent:-22.3pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The Annuities segment
manufactures, sells, and supports fixed and variable annuity products.&#160; These products are primarily sold through
stockbrokers, but are also sold through financial institutions and the Life
Marketing segment&#146;s sales force.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.3pt;text-indent:-22.3pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The Stable Value Products
segment markets guaranteed investment contracts to 401(k) and other qualified
retirement savings plans, and sells funding agreements to special purpose
entities that in turn issue notes or certificates in smaller, transferable
denominations.&#160; The segment also markets
fixed and floating rate funding agreements to the trustees of municipal bond
proceeds, institutional investors, bank trust departments, and money market
funds.&#160; During the fourth quarter of&nbsp;2003,
Protective registered a funding agreement-backed notes program with the SEC.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 22.3pt;text-indent:-22.3pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>The Asset Protection segment
markets extended service contracts and credit life and disability insurance to
protect consumers&#146; investments in automobiles and watercraft.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has an
additional segment herein referred to as Corporate and Other.&#160; The Corporate and Other segment primarily
consists of net investment income and expenses not attributable to the segments
above (including net investment income on unallocated capital and interest on
substantially all debt).&#160; This segment
also includes earnings from several small non-strategic lines of business
(mostly cancer insurance, residual value insurance, surety insurance and group
annuities), and various investment-related transactions.&#160; During&nbsp;2004, a decision was made by
management to move the surety and residual value insurance lines from the Asset
Protection segment to Corporate and Other.&#160;
All segment information presented has been amended to reflect such
change.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective uses the same
accounting policies and procedures to measure operating segment income and
assets as it uses to measure its consolidated net income and assets.&#160; Operating segment income is generally income
before income tax, adjusted to exclude any pretax minority interest in income of
consolidated subsidiaries.&#160; Premiums and
policy fees, other income, benefits and settlement expenses, and amortization
of deferred policy acquisition costs are attributed directly to each operating
segment.&#160; Net investment income is
allocated based on directly related assets required for transacting the
business of that segment. Realized investment gains (losses) and other
operating expenses are allocated to the segments in a manner which most
appropriately reflects the operations of that segment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assets are allocated
based on policy liabilities and deferred policy acquisition costs directly
attributable to each segment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There are no significant
intersegment transactions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table sets
forth total operating segment income and assets for the periods shown.&#160; Adjustments represent the inclusion of
unallocated realized investment gains (losses), the recognition of income tax
expense, income from discontinued operations, and cumulative effect of change
in accounting principle.&#160; Asset
adjustments represent the inclusion of assets related to discontinued
operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

 <tr>
  <td width="43%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:43.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note L &#151; EMPLOYEE BENEFIT PLANS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC has a defined benefit
pension plan covering substantially all of its employees, including Protective
employees.&#160; The plan is not separable by
affiliates participating in the plan.&#160;
The benefits are based on years of service and the employee&#146;s highest
thirty-six consecutive months of compensation.&#160;
PLC&#146;s funding policy is to contribute amounts to the plan sufficient to
meet the minimum funding requirements of ERISA plus such additional amounts as
PLC may determine to be appropriate from time to time.&#160; Contributions are intended to provide not only
for benefits attributed to service to date but also for those expected to be
earned in the future.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
PLC estimated that its&nbsp;2004 defined benefit pension plan expense will be
$6.4&nbsp;million, which is PLC&#146;s estimate of its expected contributions for&nbsp;2004.&#160; The measurement date used to determine the
benefit expense and benefit obligations of the plan is December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The actuarial present
value of benefit obligations and the funded status of the plan at December&nbsp;31
are as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assumptions used to
determine the net pension cost for the years ended December&nbsp;31 were as
follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="70%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:1.5in;width:70.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="57%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:57.02%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2003</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2002</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.62%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2001</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Prior to July&nbsp;1999,
upon an employee&#146;s retirement, a distribution from pension plan assets was used
to purchase a single premium annuity from Protective in the retiree&#146;s
name.&#160; Therefore, amounts shown above as
plan assets exclude assets relating to such retirees.&#160; Since July&nbsp;1999, retiree obligations
have been fulfilled from pension plan assets.&#160;
The defined benefit pension plan has a target asset allocation of 60%
domestic equities, 38% fixed income, and 2% cash and cash equivalents.&#160; When calculating asset allocation, PLC
includes reserves for pre-July&nbsp;1999 retirees.&#160; Based on historical data of the domestic
equity markets and PLC&#146;s group annuity investments, the plan&#146;s target asset
allocation would be expected to earn annualized returns in excess of 9% per
year.&#160; In arriving at the plan&#146;s 8.5%
expected rate of return, PLC has adjusted this historical data to reflect lower
expectations for equity returns.&#160; The
plan&#146;s equity assets are invested in a domestic equity index collective trust
managed by Northern Trust Corporation.&#160;
The plan&#146;s cash equivalents are invested in a collective trust managed
by Northern Trust Corporation.&#160; The plan&#146;s
fixed income assets are invested in a group annuity contract with Protective.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC also sponsors an
unfunded excess benefits plan, which is a nonqualified plan that provides
defined pension benefits in excess of limits imposed on qualified plans by
federal tax law.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, the projected benefit obligation of this plan totaled $18.1
million and $17.2 million, respectively, of which $15.5 million and $14.4
million, respectively, have been recognized in PLC&#146;s financial statements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net pension costs of the
excess benefits plan includes the following components for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

 <tr>
  <td width="55%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:55.02%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.08%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to pension
benefits, PLC provides limited healthcare benefits to eligible retired
employees until age 65.&#160; This
postretirement benefit is provided by an unfunded plan.&#160; This benefit has no material effect on PLC&#146;s
consolidated financial statements.&#160; For a
closed group of retirees over age 65, PLC provides a prescription drug
benefit.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
PLC&#146;s liability related to this benefit was $0.3 million.&#160; PLC&#146;s obligation is not materially affected
by a 1% change in the healthcare cost trend assumptions used in the calculation
of the obligation.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Life insurance benefits
for retirees from $10,000 up to a maximum of $75,000 are provided through the
payment of premiums under a group life insurance policy.&#160; This plan is partially funded at a maximum of
$50,000 face amount of insurance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC sponsors a defined
contribution retirement plan which covers substantially all employees.&#160; Employee contributions are made on a
before-tax basis as provided by Section&nbsp;401(k) of the Internal Revenue
Code. PLC established an Employee Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP) to match
voluntary employee contributions to PLC&#146;s 401(k) Plan.&#160; In 1994, a stock bonus was added to the
401(k) Plan for employees who are not otherwise under a bonus or sales
incentive plan.&#160; Expense related to the
ESOP consists of the cost of the shares allocated to participating employees
plus the interest expense on the ESOP&#146;s note payable to Protective less
dividends on shares held by the ESOP.&#160; At
December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003, PLC had committed approximately 124,682 shares to
be released to fund the 401(k) Plan match.&#160;
The expense recorded by PLC for these employee benefits was $0.6
million, $0.1 million and less than $0.1 million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC sponsors a deferred
compensation plan for certain directors, officers, agents, and others.
Compensation deferred is credited to the participants in cash, PLC Common
Stock, or as a combination thereof.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective&#146;s share of net
costs related to employee benefit plans was approximately $6.9 million, $3.8
million, and $5.4 million, in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note M &#151; STOCK BASED COMPENSATION</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Certain Protective
employees participate in PLC&#146;s stock-based incentive plans and receive stock
appreciation rights (SARs) from PLC.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Since</font> 1973, Protective has had
stock-based incentive plans to motivate management to focus on PLC&#146;s long-range
performance through the awarding of stock-based compensation.&#160; Under plans approved by share owners in 1997
and&nbsp;2003, up to 6,500,000 shares may be issued in payment of awards.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The criteria for payment of performance awards is based primarily
upon a comparison of PLC&#146;s average return on average equity and total rate of
return over a four-year award period (earlier upon the death, disability, or
retirement of the executive, or in certain circumstances, of a change in
control of PLC) to that of a comparison group of publicly held life and
multiline insurance companies.&#160; If PLC&#146;s
results are below the median of the comparison group, no portion of the award
is earned.&#160; If PLC&#146;s results are at or
above the 90th percentile, the award maximum is earned.&#160; Awards are paid in shares of PLC Common
Stock.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Performance</font> shares and performance-based stock
appreciation rights (P-SARs) awarded in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,&nbsp;2001, and&nbsp;2000,
and the estimated fair value of the awards at grant date are as follows:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Performance</font> shares are equivalent in value to
one share of PLC Common Stock times the award earned percentage payout.&#160; P-SARs convert to the equivalent of one stock
appreciation right (SAR) if earned times the award earned percentage payout. Of
the&nbsp;2000 P-SARs awarded, 87,778 have been canceled and 135,104 have been
converted to 145,910 SARs.&#160; The remaining
290,076 P-SARs will convert to SARs in&nbsp;2004 if earned.&#160; The 40,000 P-SARs awarded in&nbsp;2001 were
not earned and have been canceled.&#160; The
P-SARs, if earned and converted to SARs, expire 10 years after the grant
date.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
the total outstanding performance shares and P-SARs related to these
performance-based plans measured at maximum payouts were 660,610 and 456,286,
respectively.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Between</font> 1996 and&nbsp;2002 SARs were
granted (in addition to the P-SARs discussed above) to certain officers of PLC
to provide long-term incentive compensation based solely on the performance of
PLC&#146;s Common Stock.&#160; The SARs are
exercisable after five years (earlier upon the death, disability, or retirement
of the officer, or in certain circumstances, of a change in control of PLC) and
expire after ten years or upon termination of employment.&#160; The SARs activity as well as weighted average
base price for&nbsp;2001,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2003 is as follows:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="65%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:65.0%;">
 <tr>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.76%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="22%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:22.0%;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The </font>SARs</font>
issued in&nbsp;2001,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2003 had estimated fair values at
grant date of $0.6 million, $3.7 million, and $0.6 million, respectively.&#160; The fair value of the&nbsp;2003 SARs was
estimated using a Black-Scholes option pricing model.&#160; Assumptions used in the model were as
follows: expected volatility of 25.0% (approximately equal to that of the
S&amp;P Life and Health Insurance Index), a risk-free interest rate of 3.1%, a
dividend rate of 2.1%, and an expected exercise date of&nbsp;2009.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">PLC will pay an amount equal to the difference between the
specified base price of PLC&#146;s Common Stock and the market value at the exercise
date for each SAR.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The </font>expense</font> recorded by PLC for its stock-based compensation plans was $5.5
million, $5.2 million, and $5.6&nbsp;million in&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively.&#160; PLC&#146;s obligations of its
stock-based compensation plans that are expected to be settled in shares of PLC&#146;s
Common Stock are reported as a component of PLC&#146;s share-owners&#146; equity.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note N &#151; REINSURANCE</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective reinsures
certain of its risks with, and assumes risks from other insurers under yearly
renewable term, coinsurance, and modified coinsurance agreements.&#160; Under yearly renewable term agreements,
Protective generally pays specific premiums to the reinsurer and receives
specific amounts from the reinsurer as reimbursement for certain expenses.&#160; Coinsurance agreements are accounted for by
passing a portion of the risk to the reinsurer.&#160;
Generally, the reinsurer receives a proportionate part of the premiums
less commissions and is liable for a corresponding part of all benefit
payments.&#160; Modified coinsurance is
accounted for similarly to coinsurance except that the liability for future
policy benefits is held by the original company, and settlements are made on a
net basis between the companies.&#160; A
substantial portion of Protective&#146;s new life insurance and credit insurance
sales is being reinsured.&#160; Protective
reviews the financial condition of its reinsurers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective continues to
monitor the consolidation of reinsurers and the concentration of credit risk
Protective has with any reinsurer.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
Protective had reinsured approximately 89.6% of the face value of its life
insurance in force.&#160; Protective had
reinsured approximately 59.1% of the face value of its life insurance in force
with three reinsurers.&#160; These reinsurers
had a minimum Standard &amp; Poor&#146;s rating of AA- and a minimum A. M. Best
rating of A+.&#160; Protective has not
experienced any credit losses for the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002,
or&nbsp;2001 related to these reinsurers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective has reinsured
approximately $292.7 billion, $219.0 billion and $171.4 billion in face amount
of life insurance risks with other insurers representing $781.8 million, $546.0
million and $565.1 million of premium income for&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively.&#160; Protective has also
reinsured accident and health risks representing $61.6&nbsp;million, $61.5
million and $122.7 million of premium income for&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively.&#160; In addition, Protective
reinsured property and casualty risks representing $91.0 million, $143.9
million, and $83.3 million of premium income for&nbsp;2003,&nbsp;2002, and&nbsp;2001,
respectively.&#160; In&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002,
policy and claim reserves relating to insurance ceded of $2,230.7 million and
$2,304.9 million, respectively, are included in reinsurance receivables.&#160; Should any of the reinsurers be unable to
meet its obligation at the time of the claim, obligation to pay such claim
would remain with Protective.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003
and&nbsp;2002, Protective had paid $53.3 million and $45.5 million,
respectively, of ceded benefits which are recoverable from reinsurers.&#160; In addition, at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2003,
Protective had receivables of $66.6 million related to insurance assumed.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='',FILE='C:\JMS\cpullia\04-15437-1\task265781\15437-1-mq.htm',USER='cpullia',CD='Dec 30 13:59 2004' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In&nbsp;2002, Protective discovered that it had overpaid
reinsurance premiums to several reinsurance companies of approximately
$94.5&nbsp;million.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2002,
Protective had recorded cash and receivables totaling $69.7&nbsp;million, which
reflected the amounts received and Protective&#146;s then current estimate of
amounts to be recovered in the future, based upon the information
available.&#160; The corresponding increase in
premiums and policy fees resulted in $62.5&nbsp;million of additional
amortization of deferred policy acquisition costs in&nbsp;2002.&#160; The amortization of deferred policy
acquisition costs takes into account the amortization relating to the increase
in premiums and policy fees as well as the additional amortization required should
the remainder of the overpayment not be collected.&#160; </font>In&nbsp;2003, Protective substantially
completed its recovery of the reinsurance overpayment.&#160; As a result, Protective increased premiums
and policy fees by $18.4 million in&nbsp;2003.&#160;
The increase in premiums and policy fees resulted in $6.1 million of
additional amortization of deferred policy acquisitions costs.&#160; As a result of the recoveries, income before
income tax increased $12.3 million and $7.2 million in&nbsp;2003 and&nbsp;2002,
respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note O &#151; ESTIMATED FAIR VALUES OF
FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The carrying amount and
estimated fair values of Protective&#146;s financial instruments at December&nbsp;31
are as follows:</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.72%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.12%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.72%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.12%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:.94%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="39%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:39.64%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 20.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Derivative
  financial instruments</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

 <tr height="0">
  <td width="267" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="14" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="11" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="75" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="14" style="border:none;"></td>
  <td width="10" style="border:none;"></td>

  <td width="14" style="border:none;"></td>

  <td width="6" style="border:none;"></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Except as noted below,
fair values were estimated using quoted market prices.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective estimates the
fair value of its mortgage loans using discounted cash flows from the next call
date.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective believes the
fair value of its short-term investments and notes payable to banks
approximates book value due to either being short-term or having a variable
rate of interest.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective estimates the
fair value of its guaranteed investment contracts and annuities using
discounted cash flows and surrender values, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective believes it is
not practicable to determine the fair value of its policy loans since there is
no stated maturity, and policy loans are often repaid by reductions to policy
benefits.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:22.5pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Protective estimates the
fair value of its derivative financial instruments using market quotes or
derivative pricing models.&#160; The fair
value represents the net amount of cash Protective would have received (or
paid) had the contracts been terminated on December&nbsp;31.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

</div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Allocations of Net
Investment Income and Other Operating Expenses are based on a number of
assumptions and estimates and results would change if different methods were
applied.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Balance Sheet
adjustments represent the inclusion of assets related to discontinued
operations.</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">SCHEDULE IV &#151; REINSURANCE</font></b></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PROTECTIVE LIFE INSURANCE COMPANY
AND SUBSIDIARIES</font></b></p>

in thousands)</font></b></p>
